<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Decline for 7th Month in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. producer prices declined
for the seventh consecutive month in July, a record since the U.S.
government has kept track on the index in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department reported today that the producer
price index fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.1 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Prices paid to food producers fell by 0.2 percent -- the sixth
decline in eight months. That offset a tiny 0.1 percent increase
in energy prices.
</P>
<P>
Outside of food and energy, light truck prices fell by 0.8
percent. Computers, alcoholic beverages and floor coverings also
fell. But the cost of clothing, books and civilian aircraft rose.
</P>
<P>
So-called core prices -- excluding volatile food and energy
costs -- declined 0.1 percent in July, the fourth drop in six
months.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, monthly decreases in the U.S. producer price
index have ranged between 0.1 percent and 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The longest previous string of price declines since the
government began compiling the index in 1947 was five in a row,
from August through December 1952.
</P>
<P>
But many U.S. economists have been predicting that inflation
will rise during the second half of the year as economic growth
rebounds from a second quarter lull. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
