<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Denies Shifting Stance on Lockerbie Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The British government has flatly
denied it was looking for new ways to break an impasse over
extraditing two Libyans who were suspected of blowing up a Pan
American plane over the Scottish town of Lockerbie in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a press report that said the London government
was considering a new approach to resolve the Lockerbie issue, a
British Foreign Office spokesman dismissed the media speculation
by saying, "There has been no change in policy."
</P>
<P>
The British and U.S. governments insist that the two Libyan
suspects be tried in either Scotland or the United States and they
have rejected Libya's proposal that they should be tried by
Scottish judges under Scottish laws in a third neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The British spokesman reaffirmed London's policy that the two
Libyans "must be put on trial in Scotland or the United States."
</P>
<P>
He also explained that Prime Minister Tony Blair was "concerned
at the continuing impasse, but he is not concerned about the legal
case against the Libyans." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
