<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foodborne Diseases More Serious Than Indicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) warned today that foodborne diseases may be 300 to 350 times
more frequent than reported cases indicated.
</P>
<P>
"It is believed that hundreds of millions of people worldwide
suffer from diseases caused by contaminated food," WHO says in its
latest edition of the World Health Statistics Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
It says: "Developing countries suffer the most from a wide
range of diseases including cholera, campilobacteriosis,
Escherichia coli infections, salmonellosis, shigellosis,
brucellosis, and hepatitis A."
</P>
<P>
The annual cases of about 1.5 billion episodes of diarrhoea
among children under five years old, resulted in more than three
million deaths, WHO said. It is an indication of the seriousness
of the problem, since a significant proportion of the diarrhoea
disease cases are of foodborne origin.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that a number of industrialized countries have
experienced an increase in cases of foodborne diseases in recent
years, despite safe water supplies, sound standards of hygiene and
application of technologies such as pasteurization.
</P>
<P>
It said the emergence of Listeria monocytogenes, Escherichia
coli O157 and multi-antibiotic resistant Salmonella typhimurium
are perceived as new significant threats to public health." Japan
and Scotland saw severe outbreaks of Escherichia coli O157 last
year.
</P>
<P>
The organization also warned that foodborne diseases would
cause substantial economic costs, affecting individuals and
families, industries, health care systems and entire communities.
</P>
<P>
It cited an example when cholera broke out in Peru in
1991. More than 700 million U.S. dollars were lost in fish and
fishery products exports, and in the three months following the
start of the epidemic, 70 million dollars was lost due to closure
of food service establishments and a drop in tourism.
</P>
<P>
The WHO would continue to "promote the concept of shared
responsibility among government, industry and consumers in the
fight against foodborne diseases," said Dr Fritz Kaferstein,
Director of the WHO Program of Food Safety and Food Aid.
</P>
<P>
He urged the world to make concerted efforts in research,
regulatory control, infrastructure development, epidemiology and
training, and education to ensure the safety of food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
