<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Cleared in London Increases Sharply in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- There was a big rise in the
volume of gold cleared last month in London after the price of the
precious metal fell to a 12-year low, the London Bullion Market
Association (LBMA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The LBMA said that the average daily clearing turnover for gold
rose from 32.2 million troy ounces in June to 37 million ounces in
July.
</P>
<P>
This was only below the record 40.3 million ounces a day, worth
14 billion US dollars, cleared in February, when the average gold
price tumbled by 25 US dollars an ounce and fell below 350 US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The association reported that as a result, the average daily
value of turnover also rose to 12 billion US dollars last month
from 11 billion in June although the average price fell to 324.10
US dollars an ounce from 340.76 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The LBMA said that the big rise in the daily gold clearing
turnover in London, the international settlement center for gold
bullion, was mainly due to greater volatility of the gold price
and additional positioning and hedging.
</P>
<P>
As the association started reporting clearance data only from
October last year, there are no comparative figures for July 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
