<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Hold Senior Officials' Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean ministry said today
it has embarked on a national campaign to sensitize senior
officials from the government, non-governmental organisations and
the private sector on the implementation of the Environmental
Impact Assessment (EIA) policy.
</P>
<P>
An official of mines, environment and tourism ministry said
the ministry, in conjunction with the University of Zimbabwe's
Institute of Environmental Studies, would run week long training
courses on the policy processes before it became law.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to expose participants to the purposes, principles
and methods of EIA as an environmental planning and management
tool, as well as raise level of appreciation for those who
already know it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that participants would be provided with the capacity
to take part in the EIA implementation by carrying out and wisely
administering natural resources management studies themselves.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was exploring ways to entrench the EIA policy
into law so as to enforce Zimbabwe's mostly "environmentally
unfriendly" developers into determining potential and known
effects of proposed land/water use on the cultural, social,
economic and ecological health of the area affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
