<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn to Talk Compensation With Holocaust Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The German government and a Jewish
group will open talks on compensation to thousands of Holocaust
survivors now living in the former East Bloc.
</P>
<P>
"The government will be seeking to reach quick agreement after
the summer recess (of parliament)," government spokesman Herbert
Schmuelling said today.
</P>
<P>
Schmuelling said Chancellery Minister Friedrich Bohl and
Finance Ministry officials would meet representatives from the
Jewish Claims Conference next week to talk about the matter.
</P>
<P>
Germany has faced growing pressure to pay compensation, in the
way of pensions, to elderly Holocaust survivors in eastern Europe
and the former Soviet Union, who were excluded from reparations
made to western victims during the Cold War. Most of the up to
20,000 Holocaust victims live in the former East bloc.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's announcement of the talks came as a German Jewish leader
called on the government to pay compensation to Jewish Holocaust
survivors in eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the Holocaust survivors will die if one just keeps
talking about the issue for another two years," said Ignatz Bubis,
chairman of the Central Council of Jews in Germany. He was being
interviewed by the Berlin newspaper Tagesspiegel published today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also said that 83 United States senators would
issue an open letter to German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in an
advertisement campaign to protest against the Bonn government's
failure to approve pension claims by Holocaust survivors living in
eastern Europe and the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
The full-page advertisements, financed by the American Jewish
Committee, will be carried by the New York Times and the
International Herald Tribune in the coming weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
