<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Crude Oil Prices Forecast for Future Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- There will be a global crude oil
surplus and prices are expected to fall following the resumption
of Iraqi oil exports, Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing the latest world commodity forecast by the Economist
Intelligence Unit (EIU), the newspaper said that the average
global growth in oil consumption will be at 2.5 percent this year
compared with 2.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Of all the growth, countries outside the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development will account for more than 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that the main factor behind the bearish
outlook for the oil price is oversupply, exacerbated by Iraqi
exports.
</P>
<P>
The EIU expected the cost of oil imports to the main
industrialized countries will average 18.50 US dollars a barrel
next year and 18.30 US dollars in 1998 and prices will remain flat
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the unit believed that growth in non-OPEC oil
output, hit by a number of field delays earlier this year, will
soon resume the strong upward trend seen in recent years. It
expected non-OPEC output to rise by 3.29 million barrels per day
between 1996 and 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
