<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Commercial Farmers Support Land Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Commercial
Farmers Union (CFU) said it will continue to support the land
reform programme, but reiterated earlier warnings that market
forces should be allowed to determine price of land to be
acquired.
</P>
<P>
CFU vice-president Arthur Baisley told Zimbabwe News Agency
today the programme should be based on the
willing-buyer-willing-seller principle which would, among other
things, consider infrastructural development on the farm and land
tenure.
</P>
<P>
"The form of tenure we are looking at is not a permit to
reside, but new settlers need some form of tenure (lease with
option to purchase) so that there is some degree of
accountability and conservation of resources as well as the means
to raise finance through some form of security," Baisley said,
adding that forceful means of getting farms for resettlement
should not be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
The comments followed the announcement this week by president
Robert Mugabe that resettlement of landless Zimbabweans was going
to be accelerated with a further 1,772 farms already identified
for redistribution.
</P>
<P>
Without giving figures, Baisley said a significant number of
farms had been redistributed, and he hoped the forthcoming
resettlement exercise would be done correctly and on a
sustainable basis.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that they were in support of the new thrust of
commercial resettlement -- based on freehold title, of indigenous
farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
