<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy to Keep 2 Percent Growth Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The German economy is expected to
continue a growth rate of 2 percent in the third quarter of 1997,
to be powered solely by the booming exports, a German economic
research institute predicted today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic report issued today, the Berlin-based
German Institute for Economic Research put the German growth in
the first six months at around 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
While exports continued to expand, domestic business remained
sluggish.
</P>
<P>
The institute also challenged the notion that the current
German export boom was driven solely by the favorable exchange
rates.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the rises in exports had set in before the German
mark began its steady depreciation against the U.S. dollar,
indicating that the German industry was competitive even without
the help of the mark's weakness.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the German central bank, the Bundesbank, today also
went to defend Germany's position as a production base.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report for August, the Bundesbank noted that the
huge deficit registered by Germany in its direct investment
balance should not be traced back to the high labor costs and
sales strategies of companies alone.
</P>
<P>
Besides the higher taxes and fees, there were also other
factors including the numerous environmental regulations and the
rigidness of the labor market which had deterred foreign
investors. But corrections were already taking place in those
areas, the Bundesbank said.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank, however, admitted that further efforts were
still needed to be made by Germany in order to "correct past
mistakes and to participate successfully in the competition of
highly-developed industrial nations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
