<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Local Elections Due in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Preparations for Mozambique's
first municipal elections started amid political tension in the
country, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported today.
</P>
<P>
The elections, after which load will be taken off the central
government and resources be placed in the hands of elected
officers, are viewed by most Mozambicans as a crucial step
towards power sharing. The elections would cover 33 cities and
towns.
</P>
<P>
Manica provincial Governor Arthur Canana told Ziana today that
training of more than 100 senior government officials,
representatives from non-governmental organisations on how to run
the elections had begun this week in Chimoio.
</P>
<P>
The government was also busy teaching people about the law and
the relevance of the elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, there is political tension that has been threatening the
elections. But now we think it has been overtaken as we have
ironed out relevant issues with opposition parties," the governor
of the ruling party Frelimo said.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts viewed the elections which will take place
on December 27, as a key test for democracy in a country ravaged
by 16 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The country's first national census since 1980 would be held
in this month alongside registration for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties, on the other hand, said the date for the
elections was too close to allow proper planning, training and
preparations.
</P>
<P>
The elections, to be contested mainly by Frelimo led by
President Joaquim Chissano and Alfonso Dhlakama's Renamo, would
cost 14.36 million U.S. Dollars, coming from the donor community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
