<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Situation Deteriorating in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The food supply situation in
Sierra Leone has deteriorated and, famine is imminent if the
present insecurity persists.
</P>
<P>
In its report "Food Supply Situation and Crop Prospects in
Sub-Saharan Africa" released at a press conference here today,
the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said that there
was a real possibility of famine in that country.
</P>
<P>
The recent political upheaval erupted in May and the resulting
widespread civil unrest has aggravated the already precarious
food security situation in the West African country, the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that planting and weeding of the main crops
during the period between April and June had been seriously
disrupted as a large number of refugees had crossed into
neighbouring countries.
</P>
<P>
Prospects for food production in 1997 are very bleak and the
country will continue to need large amounts of food aid to meet
its consumption requirements, the FAO report stated.
</P>
<P>
The food supply situation has tightened in the main towns with
the price of rice, the staple food for the local people, tripling
since last May in the capital city of Freetown, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Before the upheaval, the cereal import requirement for 1997
was estimated at 260,000 tons and the food aid requirement at
80,000 tons, said the FAO, adding that "the situation is being
closely monitored". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
