<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Intensified in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign companies and relief
organizations are withdrawing from Sierra Leone due to worsening
insecurity and social situation, leaving hundreds of workers in
the south of the country jobless.
</P>
<P>
In Bo, Sierra Leone's second largest city, more than 100
workers at two international agencies, have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations, one from Britain and the other from
Germany, have already stopped their operations in the troubled
country due to insecurity and deteriorating social situation, the
British Broadcasting Company reported today.
</P>
<P>
No more relief activities have been able to continue since the
May 25 coup which ousted the elected government led by Ppresident
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, it said.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of operations of the two organizations will not
only have a huge impact on the workers who have lost their jobs,
but will seriously hamper relief and development efforts in this
area.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 300 workers of a foreign agency, World Vision
were laid off. This agency is also likely to suspend its
operations in the southern and eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports said that more than 200 people, including
some children, in the Southern Province died of starvation last
week.
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies which have been supplying food and medicine to
these areas have pulled out due to persistent cases of harassment
and seizure of supplies by security personnel.
</P>
<P>
Such an incident occurred Tuesday when relief supplies being
taken into a town in the south by catholic relief organizations
were hijacked by soldiers on the highway.
</P>
<P>
The shortage in food, medicine, fuel and other supplies is
expected to be intensified since west African countries have
reinforced economic embargo and sanction against the country in
order to oust the military junta in power.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
