<HEADLINE> SADC Day to Be Observed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Various activities have been
organized throughout the southern African region to celebrate the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) Day on August 17,
said a Zimbabwean government statement today.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, 1992, leaders of the then Southern African
Development Coordination Conference (SADCC) met in the Namibian
capital, Windoek where they signed a declaration and treaty that
gave birth to the 12-member SADC.
</P>
<P>
SADCC had for more than 10 years survived as a regional
grouping to counter then apartheid South Africa's destabilisation
activities.
</P>
<P>
SADC now seeks to transform itself into a more dynamic
organisation that will lead the region to greater cooperation and
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, ''Experience in the region and elsewhere
has shown that sustainable development is only attained when
economic growth does not leave aside socio-cultural interests.''
</P>
<P>
''Development has to take people as its central focus since
its primary concern is to meet human needs,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
It said, ''SADC has therefore decided to put people at the
centre of its development strategy by harnessing their
energies and capacities.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
