<HEADLINE> France Denies Reported Plan to Postpone Euro Launching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- France today denied a report by a
British newspaper that there is a Franco-German plan to postpone
the launching of the European single currency by one year, if
Britain is not ready to join it.
</P>
<P>
"Jacques Chirac has always recalled his attachment to the
strict respect of the calendar of the single currency," said the
French presidential office.
</P>
<P>
The French prime minister's office also said that the report is
"without any foundation."
</P>
<P>
The British newspaper Evening Standard reported today that the
French and German governments had told the British government that
they were ready to delay the launching of euro, if London does not
wish to join it now.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was directly made by President Jacques Chirac and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, said the paper, which is considered to be
well-informed.
</P>
<P>
Both France and Germany are having a difficult time fighting to
meet the budget criteria set by the Maastricht treaty for joining
the euro. 
</P>
