<HEADLINE> Food Supply Remains Difficult in Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Serious food supply
difficulties continue in Burundi, Rwanda and the eastern part of
the Democratic Republic of Congo despite the easing of the
refugee crisis in the Great Lakes Region.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. report, entitled "Food Supply Situation and Crop
Prospects in Sub-Saharan Africa" said that massive population
movements in the recent past was the main reason of the food
supply difficulties in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The report distributed at a press conference here today said
that as a result of the massive return of refugees, Rwanda would
have to feed 1.6 million more people in the second half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it said, the overall food production in 1997 in
Rwanda is estimated at 18 percent below the 1990 level.
</P>
<P>
The adverse impact of population movement and displacement on
food production is clearly seen in Rwanda and Burundi where most
fields were abandoned, the report stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Republic of Congo has been the scene of one of
the largest and the most dramatic refugee movements in Africa's
history, leading to the critical food supply situation in the
east part of the country, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
