<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Discusses Pressing Problems With Top Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today met with Chairman of the Federation Council Yegor Stroyev
and Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to discuss the most
pressing problems in the political, economic and social life of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted presidential press secretary
Sergei Yastrzhembsky as saying Yeltsin and Stroyev focused during
their meeting on problems pertaining to the draft law on religious
confessions and made necessary amendments to meet constitutional
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The press secretary said that the president and the chairman of
the Federation Council discussed a draft Taxation Code. Subjects
of the Russian Federation have different points of view on this
draft law.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Stroyev share the opinion that a number of
amendments should be made when the draft law is submitted for
discussion, which will create favorable conditions, above all, for
domestic manufacturers, Yastrzhembsky said. Besides, the Taxation
Code should contain provisions facilitating the position of those
"who have been working on land," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president and the prime minister traditionally discussed
payment of back wages owed to budgetary workers, servicemen, and
payment of pensions, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told the president that there was no lagging
behind the schedule of payments. In accordance with the
president's decision, overdue debts are being paid in a stable
rhythm as the government had promised.
</P>
<P>
According to the press secretary, a draft budget for 1998 was
discussed during the meeting. The main parameters of the 1998
state budget had been outlined. On August 21, it will be endorsed
by the government and on August 25 will be submitted to the State
Duma for approval.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin also viewed the problem of Chechnya.
Preparations for the meeting between Russian President Boris and
Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov are underway, but it is
premature to announce the date of the meeting yet, the press
secretary said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
