<HEADLINE> Fuel Scarcity Worsens in Nigerian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Worsening fuel scarcity is forcing
most of the civil servants in Abuja, the Nigerian capital to abandon
their offices in searching for oil, the official News Agency of
Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
One of the agency's reporter visited the federal secretary but
found that most of the offices were empty as officials were either
stranded in their homes, bus stops or at filling stations waiting
endlessly for fuel.
</P>
<P>
Though the capital authority has made best efforts, including
consulting with the official Fuel Distributing Company, restricting
the amount of each filling, the fuel scarcity is still worsening the
last few days, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Fuel scarcity has attacked most Nigerian cities ever since the
beginning of the year, mainly due to the lack of money to conduct
critical repairs on its major refineries, though the country is one of
the biggest oil producers worldwide, with a daily crude oil output of
2.3 million barrels. 
</P>
