<HEADLINE> France Suggests Increasing Aid if Comorans End Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- France today suggested that it
could increase its economic aid for the Indian Ocean nation of the
Comoros, if a lasting solution to the political crisis on the
archipelago is found.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux said that
France will "draw consequences from what concerns its cooperation
policy" on the basis of the results of dialogue to be held among
the Comorans.
</P>
<P>
Out of economic reasons, two of the three islands which form
the Islamic Federal Republic of the Comoros, Anjouan and Moheli
have declared "independence" and asked for the return of French
rule, which was withdrawn in 1975.
</P>
<P>
France is reducing its aid to the Comoros and plans to provide
an overall of 106 million francs (18 million U.S. dollars) of aid
to the Comoros in 1997, against 150 million francs (30 million
U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
France is cutting its overseas aid programs because of its
austerity budget plan aimed at reducing public spending and
meeting the criteria set by the Maastricht treaty for joining the
euro.
</P>
<P>
An envoy of the Organization of African Unity, Pierre Yere, has
persuaded the Comorans to accept the principle of holding dialogue
to seek a lasting solution to the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
