<HEADLINE> Nigerian Engineers Promote Locally Made Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lagos Branch of the Nigerian
Society of Engineers is planning an exhibition of locally produced
spare parts in a bid to promote the development of the manufacturing
sector.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, tagged as Sparestech '97 to be held here in October
21-24 this year, is aimed to change the attitude of Nigerians toward
made-in-Nigeria goods, which can be compared with the best in the
world, the chairman of the branch said today.
</P>
<P>
By organizing the exhibition, he said, "We intend to resuscitate our
industry, to have more people get involved in the production of local
spares, and of cause to encourage Nigerians who have the money outside
to come to this country to invest in the production of spares."
</P>
<P>
The organizers said that to promote the buying of local products
could help Nigerians improve the quality of their life, boost economic
development and increase employment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currencies used for importing will also be conserved, the
chairman added.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will highlight the country's manufactured spare
parts for vehicles and machinery mainly in the construction and power
generating industry.
</P>
<P>
To change the country's overdependence on the petroleum industry,
the Nigerian government has been encouraging local manufacturers,
producers and the public to be sensitized to the advantages of buying
made-in-Nigeria products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
