<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hussein-Netanyahu Meetings Fails to Ease Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Amman, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Today's talks between Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Jordan's King Hussein appeared short
of softening Israel's stance in the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Indeed this is a dangerous moment for the peace process, the
king said after emerging from the talks at the Royal Palace in
Jordan's Red Sea port city of Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Netanyahu insisted that the Palestinian side takes
concrete actions to improve security and combat terrorism before
Israeli-imposed closure can be relaxed.
</P>
<P>
At an obvious low key, King Hussein told reporters that he did
not expect to solve all the problems during this meeting. He
admitted that the present circumstances were dangerous because of the
"regrettable" July 30 market bombings in Jerusalem which took 15 lives.
</P>
<P>
"There was a minority on both sides trying to impose their
agenda on the majority who supported peace," the king emphasized in
the ensuing joint press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jordan is committed to peace and called for
overcoming dangerous elements in order to prevent bloodshed and devastation.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been making effort to persuade Israel to ease its
harsh sanctions against the Palestinians following the suicide
bombings and bring them closer together despite current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
As part of Jordan's diplomatic move, Crown Price Hassen has met
Netanyahu and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Tel Aviv and Cairo
respectively, and the king met Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordan would do its uttermost to support the Palestinians for
achieving a comprehensive, equitable peace founded on mutual respect
and confidence, said Hussein.
</P>
<P>
He warned against disasters ahead "if peoples of the region
would not strongly face up to throughts and ideas which cause
difficulties to them."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who arrived in Aqaba this morning on his first
official visit to an Arab nation since the Jerusalem bombings,
stressed that security was first and actions were urgently needed to
combat terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Palestinians to cooperate with Israel in such actions.
</P>
<P>
Israel meted out a full closure of the Palestinian self-rule
areas and stopped transfer of millions of dollars in tax revenues in
response to the July 30 terror attack.
</P>
<P>
The Aqaba summit was held amid expectations as Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy earlier today announced in Israel that his
country was interested in canceling measures taken against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been stalled since March when
Israel broke ground for the building of new Jewish settlements in
dispute area in East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as their
future capital.
</P>
<P>
Yet it took a turn for the worse after the suicide bombings in
West Jerusalem, for which the military wing of the Islamic miliant
group Hamas claimed responsibility, and Israel answered with a
security clampdown and restriction on the movement of Palestinian
people and goods.
</P>
<P>
Today's Hussein-Netanyahu meeting was also attended by Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan, Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali, Israeli
Foreign Minister Levy and other senior officials from both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
