<HEADLINE> Albright Says Argentina to Be Close Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said today that the United States would likely
choose Argentina as its close military ally outside the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"This status is open to other countries, including Chile,"
Albright said at a news conference with visiting Chilean Foreign
Minister Jose Miguel Insulza.
</P>
<P>
"The announcement has not yet been made but we do wish to
recognize Argintina's role," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Under the Foreign Assistance Act of 1961, the U.S. president
has authority to designate close allies, a status that does not
require U.S. help in case of attack, but these allies can buy
excess weapons from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The new designation could bring Argentina more American arms
and other military favors.
</P>
<P>
Nations already designated as close non-NATO U.S. allies
include Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Clinton administration lifted a ban on sale of
high-tech arms to Latin America. The ban was imposed in the 1970s
when most countries in the region were under military rule.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the moves by Washington in Latin America are
designed to compete with France, Russia and other European
countries for the arms market in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
