<HEADLINE> World Chemical Trade Doubles in Six Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World trade in chemicals
and chemical products amounted to some 450 billion dollars in
1990, about 10 percent of the total trade in all commodities,
according to United Nations Economic Commission for Europe.
</P>
<P>
The commission reported that the trade value doubled that of
six years earlier, representing an annual average growth of 11-12
percent.
</P>
<P>
Western Europe accounted for more than half of world imports in
chemicals and nearly two thirds of world exports, according to the
Annual Bulletin of Trade in Chemical Products published by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Chemical trade contributes some 30 billion dollars to the
Western European trade balance, while generating a 46 billion
dollar trade deficit in Asia. North America imports half as much
as Asia but exports similar amounts, the commission reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
