<HEADLINE> De Gaulle of Irish Descent: Historian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Former French President Charles de
Gaulle was a descendant of Irish immigrants in France, an Irish
historian said today.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted Pat Power, the historian, as saying
that he had found the maternal family tree of the former president
in the earldom of Down and Wicklow in eastern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He said that Marie Angelique Forde, the great-great-grandmother
of de Gaulle who was born in Lille, northern France, was Irish.
</P>
<P>
Pat said that the family of de Gaulle quit Ireland in 1691, and
that the father of Marie Angelique, Felix Forde, joined the French
army.
</P>
<P>
However, it is impossible now for people to make pilgrimage to
the home of de Gaulle in Ireland, as the house of the Forde family
was destroyed years ago, said the historian. 
</P>
