<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Says New Safety Alarms May Prevent Jet Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A new kind of altitude
warning system could prevent aircraft from crashing into mountains
and the United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) may
require all airliners to install such equipment, The New York Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The FAA said such system, already being placed in some passenger
jets by American, Alaska and United Airlines, Lufthansa and
British Airways, might have save the Korean Air Lines jumbo jet
that crashed on Guam. The crash on August 6 in a hillside near
Guam's International Airport killed more than 220 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The new system learns the aircraft's location, altitude and
course from existing navigation equipment on board. It then
compares that information with a computerized map of all the
world's mountains and predicts the length of time before an impact
would occur. It sounds a warning at 60 seconds before impact and
again, more sharply, at 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Conventional systems sometimes fail to give any warning at all.
The existing system, known as ground proximity warning systems,
became standard in the early 1970s, but they have no ability to
assess the terrain ahead of an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
It works well enough over flat terrain. But when a plane is
approaching a mountain, its height over the ground can be reduced
to zero so quickly that the system cannot provide adequate warning.
If the slope of the mountain is steep enough and the plane is
moving fast enough, the device may not provide any warning at all.
</P>
<P>
The new instrument, called an enhanced ground proximity warning
system, has the potential to make extremely rare such kinds of
accidents as the one in Guam and the one near Dubrovnik, Croatia,
that killed U.S. Commerce Secretary Ronald H. Brown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0045 </DOCNO>
