<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mysterious Fires Cause Chaos in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Nengbiao)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Lusaka was plunged into another
disturbance this morning after a third fire in two days,
swallowed the vendors' stalls in the center of Lusaka Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Vendors went on rampage in the capital city, forcing all shops
to shut down once again in three days.
</P>
<P>
Riot police fired tear gas to disperse the vendors, gunfires
could be heard and a helicopter was seen hovering above the city.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources told Xinhua that over 60 people were arrested
and more injured in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency reported that four vehicles were
damaged and three policemen were injured slightly.
</P>
<P>
Some workers went home early because of the chaos.
</P>
<P>
Calm returned later in the morning, but all shops remain
closed. In the afternoon, few vehicles and people were seen on
the streets, but groups of riot police remained there.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday evening, a mysterious fire broke out which destroyed
old Soweto market, causing a property loss of million Kwacha on
the small scale businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Police at the scene said fire fighting engines only managed to
get there nearly an hour after the fire started around 20:00
local time.
</P>
<P>
Until 07:00 this morning, fire fighters was still battling to
put out the fire.
</P>
<P>
Early Tuesday morning, another mysterious fire gutted the
entire first floor of the Zambian cabinet office, destroying
important documents, furniture and office equipment.
</P>
<P>
Fire fighters from Lusaka City Council, Zambia Air Force and
National Airport Corporation battled for more than five hours to
put out the fire.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire in the government headquarters is not
known yet.
</P>
<P>
President Frederick Chiluba rushed to inspect the damage,
saying that the fire should be served as a lesson to the lax
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Bomb experts were on the scene to prevent possible explosion.
</P>
<P>
All the documents, electrical goods like fridges and stoves,
furniture were destroyed and window panes charred.
</P>
<P>
After touring the scene, Home Affairs Minister Chitalu Sampa
said that "This is a highly sensitive matter on which I cannot
issue a statement based on preliminary investigations."
</P>
<P>
A riot broke out Monday in Lusaka when the first of the three
mysterious fires erupted in an early morning raid. Street vendors
smashed vehicles and looted some shops and stalls after their
makeshift stalls along Lumumba and Freedom roads in downtown were
burned.
</P>
<P>
Police fired tear gas cannisters to disperse the rampaging
vendors who had completely paralyzed business in the city.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the angry vendors marched to State House to ask for
explanation over what had caused the fires.
</P>
<P>
On the way to State House, they pulled down other makeshift
stalls and burnt them, destroyed all traffic lights and glass
sign posts, looted a snack caravan and a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
After being addressed at State House, the vendors returned to
the city center, but continued a looting spree and sent motorists
fleeing in all directions in confusion.
</P>
<P>
"The streets are where we make our money. This is our villages
now we can't survive," one vendor was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has accused the opposition United National
Independent Party (UNIP) of being behind the burning of street
vendors' stalls.
</P>
<P>
State House Affairs Minister Eric Silwamba told vendors that
the government had no hand in the burning of the stalls.
</P>
<P>
"It is only some overzealous people trying to politicize the
issue that are making such sweeping statements," Silwamba said.
</P>
<P>
The police authority warned that anyone loitering around
public buildings with intended purpose of sabotage will be
arrested.
</P>
<P>
Some government officials, trade union and opposition leaders
condemned the fire incidents rocking Lusaka and called on the
government to investigate the incidents and bring the culprits to
book.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday President Frederick Chiluba promised to provide
decent and modern markets and rehabilitate the existing ones to
enable both sellers and buyers to conduct their business
transactions in a conducive and hygienic environment.
</P>
<P>
When Chiluba officially opened the newly built Lusaka city
market, he told those who did not get a stall in the new market
to be patient.
</P>
<P>
Many street vendors have been doing business in Zambia's
downtown centers because of inadequate of market places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
