<HEADLINE> Ontario Hydro to Close 7 Reactors in Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Ontario Hydro announced
today that it will temporarily shutdown seven of its nuclear
reactors in a major overhaul of its production facilities.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors at North America's largest power utility
approved the overhaul in response to an extensive evaluation of
its nuclear assets conducted during the past few months.
</P>
<P>
The evaluation report, which prompted Hydro president Allan
Kupcis to resign Tuesday, gives the utility barely a passing grade
on safety but says it's still at an acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
Hydro board decided that four units at the Pickering generating
station and three at Bruce will be laid up for the next year for
overhauls.
</P>
<P>
Other reactors at the two plants will be given technical and
organizational upgrades over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The overhaul is estimated to cost Hydro up to 5.8 billion U.S.
dollars from 1997 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
To make up for the loss in production from nuclear plants,
Hydro will increase electricity production from its fossil-fuel
plants and bring back into production units that have been
mothballed at the Lennox plant.
</P>
<P>
Ontario Energy Minister Norm Sterling said today the problem is
with the way Hydro operates its plants, not with CANDU technology.
</P>
<P>
There is nothing wrong with the Canadian nuclear technology,
the minister stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
