<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Safety Alarm Device to Prevent Jet Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- All airliners in the United
States may soon be required to install a new altitude warning
system to minimize the possibility of crashes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) will publish a
proposed rule next year to make the system mandatory, the New York
Times today quoted a FAA official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thomas E. McSweeney, FAA director of aircraft certification,
said actually airliners have already begun to purchase such
equipment due to its importance.
</P>
<P>
The device could especially reduce the number of plane crashes
into mountains as it learns the aircraft's location, altitude and
course and gives warnings twice before an impact would occur.
</P>
<P>
The system compares the information with a computerized map of
the world's terrain and airports, and then displays any peaks high
enough to be of concern.
</P>
<P>
Currently, planes use radar to measure the distance plane and
the ground directly below, but such a system is less sensitive as
it may not give sufficient warning of a mountain ahead because the
distance closes too rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The only warning may come 10 seconds or less before impact
instead of two warnings that sound 60 and 30 seconds separately
ahead of impact in the new equipment.
</P>
<P>
Experts say at least two crashes are linked to warning systems.
One occurred in Guam last week with Korean Air Lines which claimed
more than 200 lives and the other with a U.S. Air Force plane
which crashed near Dubrovnik, Croatia last year, causing ex-U.S.
Commerce Secretary Ronald H. Brown's death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massachusetts Confirms First Black Supreme Court Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Governor's Council
Wednesday unanimously confirmed state Appeals Court Justice
Roderick Ireland as the first black justice in the 305-year
history of the Massachusetts Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Ireland had been nominated by Governor William Weld before Weld
resigned to pursue an ambassadorship to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
News reports quoted acting Governor Paul Cellucci as saying
that the confirmation "a great day for Massachusetts."
</P>
<P>
Ireland, 52, a native of Springfield, Massachusetts, is
considered an expert in juvenile law, and is the author of a
well-regarded textbook on juvenile justice.
</P>
<P>
Ireland became engrossed in the law while attending Lincoln
University, a historically black college in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
After graduation, Ireland went to Columbia Law School, earned
his master's degree from Harvard Law, and is working on a
doctorate at Northeastern University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
Ireland was a trial lawyer before being appointed to the
juvenile bench in 1977 by Governor Michael S. Dukakis. He was
elevated to the Appeals Court 13 years later. 
</P>
