<HEADLINE> EU Appeals for Cessation of Violence in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union, a major
donor of aid to Cambodia, today appealed for immediate cessation
of violence in that country.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union expressed concern over the situation in
Cambodia and extended support to the mediation efforts made by the
ASEAN, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers, at a meeting held Monday in Singapore,
did not rule out the possibility of calling an informal meeting
for all the parties involved with a view to restoring stability in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's political framework was put in place by an
international agreement in Paris in 1991 that ended decades of
domestic conflicts. The coalition government took form from
U.N.-supervised elections two years later.
</P>
<P>
The EU appreciates the role played by King Norodom Sihanouk who
offered to abdicate if stability can be restored in the country.
</P>
<P>
But army units loyal to ousted First Prime Minister Prince
Ranariddh were reportedly preparing an offensive against
opposition troops controlling a zone in the northwest of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The fighting is expected to escalate as both sides attempt to
grab as much territory as possible before monsoons intensify to
halt military operations for a few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
