<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Medalists to Vie for Final Spots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Olympic gold and silver
medalists at last year's Atlanta Olympic Games Cuba and China will
join Japan and Italy in the Hong Kong leg of this year's World
Women's Volleyball Grand Prix which starts here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Vittel Cup event is one of the five legs for the
preliminary stages for this year's Grand Prix series, which offer
a total purse of 1.5 million U.S. dollars. The top three teams
from the stages will join host Japan in the grand finals set for
August 29-31 in Kobe, Japan.
</P>
<P>
After two stages held simultaneously in Macao and Seoul, teams
from Russia, Sough Korea and China lead in top three of the Grand
Prix standings.
</P>
<P>
The six Vittel Cup matches are to be played in the Hong Kong
Coliseum. The event is organized by the Volleyball Association of
Hong Kong, China, and sponsored by Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
China, winners of the Macao leg for the last two years, made a
flying start this year by beating Italy and the United States. But
Russians proved to be stronger with their third straight win in
the three-day leg in Macao, beating China three sets to one
Sunday. Russia won the leg and China was runners-up.
</P>
<P>
Cuba, world number one and Olympic champion, felt difficult
getting into the Seoul leg of the Grand Prix. It finished third
after winner South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
China and Cuba never failed to make to the World Volleyball
Grand Prix Finals in the last five years. Japan made the finals
only once, in 1993, and the Italians are trying to reach their
first final.
</P>
<P>
Another three-day leg is to get started Friday in Chinese
Taipei, with the participation of Russia, the United States, South
Korea and the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
