<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Island Province to Balance Economy and Environment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The groundwater level in Haikou,
Hainan Province, which has been dropping in the past few years,
has returned to what it was in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"The rise indicates that the ecosystem of this island province
is improving," said Feng Tinghan, senior engineer and head of the
province's Geological Environment Monitoring Station.
</P>
<P>
Feng attributes the recovery to the province's effort to
upgrade its programs for water use, growing trees, and conserving
water resources.
</P>
<P>
Hainan became one of China's five special economic zones in
1988. Soon after, the once agriculture-oriented region has become
the country's largest construction site, flooded by industrial
projects and businesses.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to build some heavy industrial projects involving
natural gas, fertilizer, paper pulp, oil refining, and steel, to
bring in an estimated excess of 40 billion yuan in industrial
output by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The province has given equal priority to economic development
and environmental protection. It has adopted more than 20
regulations and policies concerning environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hainan closed 75 small factories that were polluters
to eliminate 5,600 tons of waste water, 18 million cubic meters of
waste gas, and 84 million tons of solid waste.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, more than 400 older enterprises were required to
treat their pollutants within three years, and faced shutdown if
they failed to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Island Province to Balance Economy and Environment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To improve the environment, a 15-billion-yuan fertilizer
project, the largest of its kind in China, scheduled to be located
in the tourist city of Sanya will be built elsewhere. As a result
of the change, the investor had to spend more than a billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Economic losses can be measurable and affordable, but we
cannot estimate and make up for the sacrifices that a polluted
environment would bring," said an expert who participated in the
decision on relocating the factory.
</P>
<P>
And at least another three large projects each with 50 million
to 150 million yuan of investment have been canceled in Sanya due
to failure to meet environmental protection standards.
</P>
<P>
"Those measures are doing well to prevent the economically
booming province from being polluted," said Cheng Dongwei, a
government official in charge of environmental protection and
resources.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 10 years, the province has recovered more than
200,000 ha of tropical forests, and established 73 nature
reserves, covering 2.68 million ha. Consequently, local gibbons,
mangrove forests, and other rare species of plants and animals are
well-protected, and the forest coverage rate is more than 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
A non-governmental organization for environmental protection has
been formed, and in 76 primary and secondary schools, courses on
environmental protection are now offered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Oldest Human Skeleton to Be Displayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A 20,000-year-old human skeleton,
the oldest found in Egypt, will be shown to the public for the
first time in October.
</P>
<P>
The skeleton will be exhibited at the new Nubia Museum that
will be inaugurated by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Aswan,
Upper Egypt, on October 11.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency today quoted Head of the museum's
Scientific Committee Ibrahim al-Nawawi as confirming that the
skeleton dates back to the stone age.
</P>
<P>
The skeleton was unearthed by a German excavation team in a
valley in the West Desert, northern Aswan in 1982.
</P>
<P>
It was unearthed headless and the parts found were only the
neck, the torso and the limbs. It had been sent to the U.S. for a
year where it underwent thorough studies and tests to define its
age, Nawawi said.
</P>
<P>
It will be displayed together with 2,000 other pieces of
antiquities selected from museums across the country to depict
Egypt's 5,000-year civilization, according to Nawawi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Goods Smuggling on Rise in Nepal-India Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Smuggling of goods is on the
rise in Nepal-India border, the daily Kathmandu Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The items being smuggled into India from Nepal include cows,
oxen and buffaloes.
</P>
<P>
Being smuggled into Nepal from India are cloth, steel utensils,
TV sets, electronic goods, chocolate, biscuits and powder milk,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Police in Morang district of eastern Nepal said it is the petty
smugglers who are involved in such small-scale smuggling
activities.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal-India Joint Working Group met in mid-July in
Kathmandu on border management, and agreed to improve the
management of the 1,750-kilometer-long open border in order to
control movement of undesirable elements and illicit movement of
goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
