<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq: Supply of Medicine Far From Enough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today said the inadequate
supply of medicine under its oil-for-food deal with the United
Nations is the main reason for a complex health situation.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak said in a press
release that the medicine sent to Iraq during the first stage of
the deal stood less than 10 percent of the need.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allowed Iraq to export 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil in six months for buying food and badly
needed medicines. The first stage of the deal went into effect
last December and on June 8 the U.N. Security Council agreed to
extend it for another six months.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has signed more than 550 contracts with foreign countries
for importing medicine and medical requirements in the first stage
of the oil-for-food deal which was signed in May last year,
according to Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
But he complained that only 84 percent of these contracts were
ratified by the U.N. and the arrivals of medicine were delayed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the incidence of several epidemic diseases,
including cholera and infantile paralysis has increased in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The environmental conditions are also deteriorating, making the
health situation more complexed, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The purification of potable water and elimination of chemical
wastes have become big problems in the country, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's GDP Slightly Up in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The 15-nation European Union
posted a slight positive growth as a whole as Eurostat, the EU's
statistics arm, today reported a 0.1-percent growth in the first
quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
The growth was compared to the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The small increase was attributed to a slight upward move on
the part of private consumption offset by the slowdown of the
gross fixed capital formation.
</P>
<P>
Available figures showed that only Britain, Spain and France
recorded a rise in the January-March period whereas Denmark,
Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Finland and Sweden all registered
negative growths.
</P>
<P>
On an annual basis, Eurostat reported, the EU's GDP rose 1.6
percent from the first quarter of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
