<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel Calls for Tough Stand on Foreigner Inflows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has called on the government to take a hard line in curbing the
massive inflows of foreigners which, he said, was one of the
reasons for Germany's ever-continuing high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"We must be firmer both in sending back illegal foreigners
living here, and limiting immigration where it is possible and
justified," Waigel said in an interview with the German
mass-circulation newspaper, Bild.
</P>
<P>
There should be a cap on immigration and the deportation of
rejected asylum-seekers should become a rule with no exceptions,
Waigel said in the interview published today.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the countries which refused to take back
their deported nationals should face cuts of development aid from
Bonn. He did not name these countries.
</P>
<P>
Waigel noted that Germany was suffering from the highest rate
of immigration in the world.
</P>
<P>
Germany's jobless rate hit a post-war record of 11.4 percent in
July, highlighting economic and political strains on Bonn only a
year ahead of the legislative election. A total of 4.354 million
people were unemployed last month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking as government and oppositions were juggling for
position in the run-up for next year's election campaign, Waigel
said immigration was a problem not only for the job market.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has so far failed to push through a sweeping tax reform
package while facing a sharp decline of the mark against the
U.S. dollar, and fears over Germany's ability to meet strict
criteria to qualify for a single European currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
