<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive to Visit Six Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive
 of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), will visit
Malaysia, Singapore, the United States, Japan, Belgium and the
United Kingdom in the next two months, an official release said
today.
</P>
<P>
It said that the purpose of the visit is to renew ties with
Hong Kong's trading partners and update them on developments in
Hong Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
During these visits, Tung will call on political and business
leaders, and brief them on the smooth transition in Hong Kong to
demonstrate Hong Kong people's pride to return to China and their
confidence in "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" under the
"one country, two systems" concept, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Tung will be in Kuala Lumpur on September 3 and call on Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad; then he will be visiting Singapore on
September 4 and 5 and call on Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Tung will be in the United States from September 9 to 11,
visiting Washington and New York. In Washington, Tung looks
forward to meeting with President Clinton. He will also officiate
at the opening ceremony of the new office premises of the Hong
Kong Economic and Trade Office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Tung will be in Tokyo from October 15 to 17. He will call on
ministers, parliamentarians and senior officials of the Japanese
government.
</P>
<P>
On October 19, he will leave for Europe and visit Brussels and
London before returning to Hong Kong on October 23.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, Tung will call on President of the European
Commission Jacques Santer and attend the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council Annual Dinner in Europe. He also hopes to meet
 with Belgian ministers.
</P>
<P>
In London, Tung looks forward to meeting with Prime Minister
Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
The release said that the Chief Executive will be speaking at a
 number of functions in various destinations. He will reassure
overseas audiences of Hong Kong's continued role as an active
regional and global player in international trade, commerce and
finance.
</P>
<P>
Tung will also welcome international investors to come to Hong
Kong to take advantage of the enormous business opportunities here
 as Hong Kong becomes part of China, the release said.  
</P>
