<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steady Seven-Month Growth In China's Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China had a total of 172.26
billion US dollars worth of foreign trade in the first seven
months, up 14.1 percent from last year, according to General
Customs Administration statistics.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 26.1 percent to 96.4 billion US dollars, while
imports stayed at 75.86 billion US dollars, a rise of only 1.9
percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Import volume declined on a monthly basis, but China achieved
its first import growth this year in July, with 12.82 billion US
dollars, 13.4 percent more than that of last year and 13.8 percent
more than for June.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade was characterized by a growth in general trade and
processed goods, and faster growth of exports by state-owned
enterprises than overseas-funded companies.
</P>
<P>
State-owned businesses exported 54.49 billion US dollars worth
of goods, up 25.7 percent while overseas-funded businesses
recorded a 24.9 percent rise to 39.23 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
But state-owned business imports were 32.83 billion US dollars,
down 2.3 percent, and overseas-funded company imports increased
6.9 percent to 41.08 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and electronic products exports exceeded imports for
the first time, rising 24.6 percent to 30.56 billion US dollars,
32 percent of the total export volume.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
