<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Involvement in Somalia Met with Varied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The political status in
Mogadishu, the Somali capital, has been struck by the U.S.
attitude towards the on-going reconciliation attempts.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to the five co-chairmen of the National
Salvation Council established in Ethiopia early this year, the
American Assistant Secretary of State, George E. Moose, said
America will watch with interest the progress towards Bossaso
conference to be held in November.
</P>
<P>
He said he will find it difficult to understand if any single
Somali leader remains unready to make the political compromises
necessary to achieve national reconciliation, the first step
toward the renaissance of Somali.
</P>
<P>
Moose added that his government endorses Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi's initiatives in the reconciliation efforts for Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to this letter, the faction led by Hussein Mohamed
Aidid has strongly criticized the American stance in the Somali
politics.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, the interior minister of Hussein
Aidid's government, said America should not be deceived by
Ethiopia who deliberately sides with the factions opposing his
government.
</P>
<P>
Qanyare said Ethiopia is not only partial in the Somali
politics but also occupies parts of Somalia's territory,
violating the territorial integrity of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
However, Qanyare said according to the agreement they signed
with Ali Mahdi Mohamed in Cairo in late May this year, his
government accepts a national reconciliation conference provided
that the criteria and its venue be agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Qanyare said the letter by the Americans will not change
anything about their political position and will in no way go to
Bossaso for any meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, the north Mogadishu faction led by Ali
Mahdi Mohamed has appreciated the American support in the
anticipated Bossaso meeting for the formation of a legitimate
Somali government.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Sheikh Ahmed Kadare, Information Secretary for Ali
Mahdi, said they welcome the first American involvement in the
Somali politics.
</P>
<P>
Kadare has called on U.S. to contribute a tangible support to
the forthcoming Bossaso meeting and appealed to the European
Union to take similar measures for the common good of the
Somalis.
</P>
<P>
On the streets of the Somali capital, both the politicians and
the ordinary people have been talking about the possible
consequences of the American position towards the current
political maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The ordinary citizens have similarly been discussing the issue
in the tea-shops and business stalls following the BBC Somali
Service broadcast of the American letter in Somali language.
</P>
<P>
People have expressed mixed feelings about the current
political uncertainty and the message the letter conveyed.
</P>
<P>
They ruled out any military involvement by the Americans but
indicated fear against the use of African soldiers especially
Ethiopians once a military option is taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
