<HEADLINE> Sino-US Power Project In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The second phase of work on a
jointly funded Sino-US power plant at Jingyuan in northwest
China's Gansu province has been completed and two generating units
with an installed capacity of 600,000 kilowatts are operating.
</P>
<P>
This helps ease the power shortages in northwest China, from
this area about 140 kilometers from the provincial capital of
Lanzhou, near the Jingyuan Coal Mine.
</P>
<P>
To ease the power crunch in the northwest network, the country
decided in 1993 to ask the US's Westinghouse Electric to jointly
fund the second-phase of construction.
</P>
<P>
The US company provided 30 percent of the 2.5 billion yuan
dollar cost.
</P>
<P>
The two new generating units are computerized. One is fully
operational and the other is undergoing trials. 
