<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmer Uses Lawyers For Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Longyun, a 52-year-old
farmer in Ningbo, a port city in China's Zhejiang Province, ran
into contract problems with his hired hands, so he did something
new - he got some lawyers to represent him.
</P>
<P>
The farmer had made quite a lot of money after years of hard
work on his 53 mu of land (3.6 hectares) in Ningbo, but he was
having more contract disputes with hired hands and problems of
quality in the materials he used.
</P>
<P>
"Now I can sleep more soundly at night after I pasted a notice
on the wall about hiring two lawyers to represent me at the
beginning of the year. Its effects were quickly felt, and now no
one tries to find faults with me any more," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The old man's schooling had stopped after two years and he knew
nothing about the world of law, as was the case with millions of
Chinese farmers before him, but, he says, "I've learned what laws
mean from the lessons that life taught me."
</P>
<P>
Last year, when he was accused of being a thief who stole
neighbor's cotton, it cost him a lot of time and money to set the
matter straight. "It's quite tiresome and time-consuming to deal
with these problems by yourself. I had to delay my work to deal
with the case," he explains.
</P>
<P>
So, he turned to the law for help and hired the two lawyers, Li
Yuefei and Chen Shiyao, as consultants. They can sign contracts
and handle other daily affairs on his behalf, allowing him to
focus all his attention on his work and leave his troubles behind.
</P>
<P>
Now some of Zhao's neighbors have also been turning to lawyers
for help when they run into troubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
