<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mutual Interests to Ensure Success of Jiang's US Visit By Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The fact that China and the
United States are seeking common strategic interests will ensure
the success of Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visit to US
this fall.
</P>
<P>
Four groups of prominent figures from the US political circle
have visited China for meetings with top Chinese leaders since the
beginning of August.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders and members of American delegations discussed
the forthcoming US visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
bilateral relations as well as various other issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States attach great importance to the
visit and are seeking shared strategic interests to ensure the
substantial success of the visit, the first US visit by a
Chinese head of state in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Recent US dignitaries visiting China include Assistant to the
US President for National Security Affairs Samuel Berger, who
came to prepare for Jiang's trip; President Pro Tempore of
the United States Senate Strom Thurmond; a delegation of the US
House of Representatives International Relations Committee led by
chairman Benjamin Gilman; and a delegation from US Center for
Democracy, jointly headed by chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Subcommittee on East Asian and Pacific Affairs Craig
Thomas and center president Allen Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noted successive visits by US political
figures, and the fact that the high-level reception granted to
each demonstrates the anticipation of both sides on expanding
stable, healthy and cooperative Sino-US ties into the 21st
century, and the landmark impact of Jiang's impending visit.
</P>
<P>
Observers say China and the United States should approach their
relationship from a strategic viewpoint and work diligently to
expand mutual understanding, enhance mutual trust, and narrow
differences to create a common future.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 has witnessed steady improvements of Sino-US ties
and significantly increasing exchanges at different levels.
</P>
<P>
US Vice-President Al Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright have visited China, in addition to trips by Speaker of
the US House of Representatives Newt Gingrich and dozens of other
congressmen.
</P>
<P>
Meetings between leaders from the two countries have in the
past and will undoubtably continue to inject new impetus into the
advancement of bilateral relations. The smooth development of
Sino-US relations since the second half of last year have laid a
sound foundation for the success of Jiang's visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
