<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, ROK Streamline Nuclear Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the Republic of
Korea (ROK) have taken the first steps towards a new agreement
which facilitate transfer of Australian uranium to third countries
for purposes such as enrichment.
</P>
<P>
Australia and ROK officially exchanged diplomatic notes this
week, which will lead to a new agreement as soon as domestic
political requirements are satisfied, the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) today quoted the Australian Department of Foreign
Affairs and Trade (DFAT) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ROK is a major customer for Australian uranium, accounting
for an increasing share of exports, AAP said, but it did not go
into details.
</P>
<P>
The agreement relates to nuclear material before it is actually
placed in reactors, and is similar to agreements Australia has
with other uranium customers.
</P>
<P>
Such material often has to be processed in separate countries
at different stages of the nuclear fuel cycle, with Australia
agreeing to transfers for purposes such as conversion, enrichment
to less than 20 percent of uranium 235 and fuel fabrication.
</P>
<P>
"Until now requests by the ROK to retransfer to third countries
nuclear materials subject to the 1979 'Australia-ROK agreement
concerning the cooperation in peaceful uses of nuclear energy and
transfer of nuclear material' have required Australia's written
consent on a case by case basis," DEAT said.
</P>
<P>
"Under the new agreement such consent is expected in advance on
a generic basis for retransfers for specified purposes at the
front end of the nuclear fuel cycle."
</P>
<P>
DFAT said the agreement would not detract from
non-proliferation and security objectives and would preserve
Australia's right to approve retransfers and to designate
countries to which transfers could be made.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Decides Not to Defend Its Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JASKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
announced here today that the Monetary Authority would float the
Indonesian rupiah by removing the spread of the rupiah exchange
rate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Finance Minister Mar'ie Mohamad
said that the purpose of the move is to reduce the negative
affects on the rupiah caused by speculative activities. The
rupiah's value will be decided by the market.
</P>
<P>
In a swift reaction, the rupiah tumbled to a record low of
2,775 to the U.S. dollar this afternoon, reducing 112 points from
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for the rupiah to breach the 2,700 level.
The currency Wednesday closed at 2,645 to the greenback after
hitting a record low of 2,682.
</P>
<P>
The new policy is suitable to the development in monetary
market in Southeast Asia, the minister said, adding that Malaysia
had earlier abandoned its original policy to defend its currency.
</P>
<P>
Experiences in the region indicated that the government
intervention has no obvious effects as "the regional factor" is
the main factor affecting the value of the rupiah, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, if it is necessary, the government would
exert its influence on the monetary market through indirect
financial and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
To defend the rupiah fluctuation which began in mid-July, the
central bank has widened the spread of the rupiah exchange rate
from 8 percent to 12 percent. The government has also sold 1.5
billion U.S. dollars and raised overnight interest rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
