<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mutual Interests to Ensure Success of Jiang's US Visit (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Observers note that the common and major interests of the two
powers have intensified rather than weakened despite major changes
in the international situation since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaqiu, director of the State Council Foreign Affairs
Office, and Samuel Berger jointly expressed hope that the two
countries will maintain world peace and stability and avoid new
wars. They noted that both countries are interested in expanding
strategic dialogues and cooperation, and also expressed hope for
peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific Region, as well as
economic cooperation and development.
</P>
<P>
The two officials noted that the two countries are becoming
increasingly complementary in economic and trade development, and
that vast untapped potential exists for bilateral cooperation in
education, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The officials pointed to the fact that many Americans
understand the shared strategic interests between China and the
United States, and they agreed that the two countries need to
expand channels for dialogue, especially high-level dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with "Newsweek International", US
Ambassador to China James Sasser said the two countries share
numerous areas of strategic interest, including maintaining peace
and security in the Asia-Pacific Region, dealing firmly with
terrorism, and cooperating in environmental protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
Sasser also noted that the forthcoming summit "will establish a
strategic framework wherein the United States and China can relate
to each other in coming years".
</P>
<P>
China and the US already share a common understanding that
developing stable and sound bilateral relations is in the best
interests of people in the two countries, as well as people around
the world.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin's trip to the United States will not only
verify the restoration of high-level dialogues in the capital
cities of the two countries, but will signal that bilateral ties
have ushered in a new era of development.  
</P>
