<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainfall in Hong Kong Breaks Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong recorded a
cumulative rainfall of 1,529.6 mm for the two consecutive months
of June and July this year, the Hong Kong Observatory said today.
</P>
<P>
On the heal of a wet June, July continued to have heavy rains
and frequent thunderstorms when an active trough of low pressure
lingered on the South China coast. In July, the total rainfall
reached 746 mm, the fourth highest for the month, while the bright
sunshine duration stood 125.1 hours, the shortest in history.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon Victor, the worst in 14 years in Hong Kong, made a
direct hit on the city on the last day of July.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Observatory said that a trough of low pressure
controlled South China coastal areas this summer, bringing
unsettled weather and exceptionally high rainfall to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Observatory said that although the first half of August
has not passed yet, it is official that the first eight months of
1997 has set another rainfall record in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
By five o'clock this morning, the accumulated rainfall since
the beginning of this year has reached 2611.3 mm, surpassing the
previous record of 2610.4 mm in 1973, the Observatory reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Normally, Hong Kong has annual rainfall of 2,214.3 mm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
