<HEADLINE> Feature: Pakistan Celebrates Independence Day with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today celebrated the
50th anniversary of its independence with a renewed pledge to
enter the 21st century as a progressive, democratic and
self-reliant country.
</P>
<P>
The 50th birthday of Pakistan, dawned with the booming of
31-gun salute in the federal capital, has witnessed an unusual
enthusiasm among the people for the golden jubilee celebrations.
</P>
<P>
About 15,000 of people of all age group, wearing bright and
glittering dresses and raising the national flags high over their
heads, jampacked a grand square in front of the Parliament House
where Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif hoisted at 8 a.m. the crescent
and star flag at a colorful special ceremony marking the
historical moment.
</P>
<P>
As hundreds of multi-colored balloons were released to the
bright blue sky, ministers, chiefs of all services, senior civil
and military officials joined the Prime Minister in singing the
national anthem accompanied by a band of children in national
ceremonial dress.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, sirens blared throughout the country and the elite
gathered outside the parliament building as the nation observed
one-minute's silence at 7.59 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Making his second speech of the day after heralding the golden
jubilee with a midnight televised address, Sharif envisioned a
"glorious future" for the nation of about 140 million people,
which was founded on August 14, 1947.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan will enter the 21st century with the determination to
become a "great nation which should serve as an inspiring model
for other nations", Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
"Gone are the days of despondency and despair," he declared,
adding now the economy of the country is showing sign of revival
as there is political stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make a modern Islamic welfare state on scientific
lines which should be free of exploitation and based on tolerance,
justice and forbearance."
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister invited the talented youth of the country to
come forward and take part in nation building.
</P>
<P>
"I invite my youth, hope for the entire nation, to contribute
their energies to make Pakistan a developed country free of
ignorance, disease and backwardness," he said.
</P>
<P>
The usually tranquil Islamabad was pleasantly noisy today. All
the public and private buildings in the federal capital were
decorated with spectacular lights and buntings. Long queues of
cars and traffic jams became frequent.
</P>
<P>
Most drivers played the national songs at full volume in their
cars while children and youngsters, some of them riding tops of
the cars, shouted patriotic slogans. These indeed created a
somewhat sensational scene.
</P>
<P>
"This is a historical moment of promise and hope for the people
of Pakistan," said a senior government official when asked what he
was thinking at Today's special occasion. "It is indeed pretty
encouraging to see the national spirit so high."
</P>
<P>
"It was evident that despite all the hardships and financial
constraints faced by the common people, they still have strong
confidence in the country's future," said the middle-aged
official.
</P>
<P>
"Today is the day of jubilation and it also demands
reflection," he said. "The government should work earnestly with
the hardworking people to make the country strong and prosperous."
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
