<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golden Summer for Egyptian Gold Lovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A drop in world gold prices this
year means that consumers no longer need to be born with a silver
spoon in their mouths to make a purchase, the Egyptian newspaper
Al Ahram reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptians and Arabs, whose rising demand for gold during the
summer traditionally drives up the price of the metal, look set to
a good bargain this season as gold prices dropped to their lowest
levels in years, according to the English weekly.
</P>
<P>
The price of one gram of 18 carat gold stood at roughly 34
Egyptian pounds (10 U.S. dollars) last year, but dropped to 27
pounds (7.9 dollars) by this summer.
</P>
<P>
Part of the reason behind the decline in prices on the Egyptian
gold market is a 20 percent tariff cut on gold bullion which came
into effect earlier this year, according to a jeweller.
</P>
<P>
The drop in gold prices in Egypt is also linked to the
declining price of gold on the international market, where the
cost of gold has fallen to its lowest level in 12 years, reaching
315 dollars per ounce on the London precious metals exchange.
</P>
<P>
Similar cuts in prices have also been registered on the Arab
markets, with a kilogram of 24 carat gold in Saudi Arabia, for
example, now selling for 38,000 riyals (10,059 dollars) compared
with 48,000 riyals (12,706 dollars) the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
Further fueling this decrease in global prices is the fact that
businessmen and investors have turned to dollar deposits instead
of gold, according to Sultan Abu Ali, a former Saudi minister of
economy.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever the interest on dollar deposits increases, the price
of gold decreases," he noted.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the supply of gold on the international market,
with a number of countries such as Germany, Russia and Australia
selling a sizable chunk of their gold stock for a variety of
reasons, has also helped drive down prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0115 </DOCNO>
