<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan and Swedish
governments have signed two cooperation agreements in the
economic and health fields with a investment of 24 million U.S.
dollars, the Angola News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The accords were sealed here Wednesday by Angolan Foreign
Minister Sebastiad Isata and Lena Sundh, Swedish ambassador to
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Isata underscored the importance of the cooperation between
his country and Sweden, saying that the two agreements will help
the Angolan people overcome their current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, the Swedish ambassador expressed his
country's willingness to participate in Angola's postwar
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that the smooth implementation of the two
pacts relies on the cooperation of the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
Under the economic agreement, the two countries will invest 10
million Dollars in Angola's northern province of Malange to
promote agricultural production and resettle refugees displaced
during tee 20 years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The health agreement provides that Sweden will invest 14
million Dollars in two and a half years to set up maternity
hospitals and train nurses in the capital. 
