<HEADLINE> Ramos Unveils Village to Mark ASEAN's 30th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
inaugurated here today an ASEAN village to mark the 30th founding
anniversary of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
A highlight of the week-long celebration of the ASEAN's 30th
birthday, the village is a garden with miniature structures
representing each of the nine ASEAN member countries, including
Laos and Myanmar which were admitted to the grouping last month.
</P>
<P>
A portion of the garden is devoted to honoring the five
founding fathers of the ASEAN through five bronze busts, one of
which was the late father of President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The village also features two memorial plaques of the 1967
Bangkok Declaration which gave birth to the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN was founded on August 8, 1967 with five original
members -- Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and
Thailand. Brunei, the sixth member, joined the ASEAN in 1984 and
Vietnam, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos said in his inauguration address that as the
ASEAN moves into the next century, it faces the daunting task of
sustaining its dynamism and maintaining its good record.
</P>
<P>
"It (the village) points to us even more to the labors still
before us -- of completing our dream of ASEAN encompassing all the
10 countries of Southeast Asia and of bringing ASEAN into the
forefront of the 21st century," he said. 
</P>
