<P>
In spite of the expanding economy, Hang Seng Bank revised
downward its inflation rate projection for the year, from 7 to 6.5
percent, as a result of the drop in import prices helped by the
strong dollar.
</P>
<P>
But the report cautioned that domestically-generated price
pressures are expected to pick up in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
It said that in light of the economic recovery in Hong Kong's
major export markets, export growth is expected to rebound mildly
in the second half of the year. The forecast for total export
growth in 1997 was lowered from 9.7 to 4.6 percent due to the
lackluster export performance in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicts that the surge in the transshipment of
goods arranged by Hong Kong traders will continue, leading to
continued strong demand for trade-support services such as
banking, finance and shipping.
</P>
<P>
The report also forecast that building activities in Hong Kong
would continue to accelerate, reflecting both private and public
sector efforts to boost flat supply.
</P>
<P>
Investment in plant and machinery is also projected to maintain
steady growth, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
