<HEADLINE> HK Manufacturers Expect More Orders in 2nd-Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong manufacturers expect
a slight increase in volume of orders in the second half of 1997
compared with the same period of 1996, according to a government
survey released today.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers in electronic, electrical, machinery and printing
industries generally expect a moderate rise in volume of orders,
whereas producers in apparel, metal and textile industries
anticipate stable or lower volumes of order, showed the
Half-yearly Business Prospects Survey by the Census and Statistics
Department.
</P>
<P>
Profit margins are expected to edge down, while export value to
go up moderately in the later half of 1997 over the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted every six months, collects views of firms
on the short-term prospects of various business sectors and
predicts Hong Kong's economic performance in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Usually, the poll covers about 300 firms from major
manufacturing industries, import and export trade, banking and
construction sectors. 
</P>
