<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Elephant Population at 4,000-4,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The latest census taken by the
Wildlife Conservation Department shows that the present elephant
population of Sri Lanka is from 4,000 to 4,500, according to the
department sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that an earlier survey conducted on an
improper basis had inaccurately estimated the elephant population
at 2,500-3,000.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest census conducted on a scientific basis
including the internationally accepted "dung count" and personal
data gathered from field interviews with villagers in
elephant-populated areas, shows that in fact there are 4,000 to
4,500 elephants in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
They also revealed that elephant corridors are being
established connecting the country' national parks at
Lunugamwehera, Uduwalwe and Yala in the south up to Kumana and
Lahugalle in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
These corridors will be officially declared elephant corridors
and protected areas by the government.
</P>
<P>
The big advantage here is that elephants can move from one
protected area to another particularly in times of drought in
their usual habitat, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
There were over 10,000 elephants at the start of this century
in Sri Lanka. However, about 60 to 70 elephants are killed every
year by predators who go for tusks and by farmers defending their
crops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
