<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Increased expectations of
another cut to official interest rates today caused the Australian
dollar to finish lower against the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics today released a breakdown
of its average weekly ordinary time earnings data for the three
months to May.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the numbers showed wages growth was exerting
very little pressure on the economy and markets interpreted the
data as lending support to a further rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia last cut interest rates on July
30, bringing the official cash rate from 5.5 to 5.0.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 74.41 U.S. cents compared
with 74.61 late Wednesday after trading in a range of 74.29 to
74.60.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank's senior economist John Peters said Westpac
believed that over the next few months the market would move to
price a 4.5 percent cash rate into the yield curve.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 86.50 from 86.79 against the
Japanese yen and at 1.3701 from 1.3843 against the German mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
