<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister Repeats Call For Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has shrugged off a rejection from Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
repeated a call for a German cabinet reshuffle soon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Bild, Waigel said a
shake-up would strengthen Kohl's 17-member cabinet and improve his
chances to win the next general elections due in September next
year.
</P>
<P>
Waigel also rejected speculations that by proposing a cabinet
reshuffle, he was actually seeking Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel's
job. "I enjoy my job," he said.
</P>
<P>
Suggesting that some ministers did want to leave but were just
trying to hang on to their jobs until the election, Waigel urged
Kohl to drop them now for the benefit of the whole ruling
coalition.
</P>
<P>
A similar call was made by Waigel in an interview with the
German news magazine Der Spiegel during the weekend. But Kohl, who
is now on vacation in Austria, was quoted by a government
spokesman as saying on Monday that a cabinet reshuffle was not
necessary at the moment.
</P>
<P>
In view that the government's tax reform plan has been foiled
by the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the
economy is growing too slowly to bring down Germany's record
unemployment, analysts said that a shake-up in Kohl's cabinet was
overdue and could help reverse the government's steep slide in
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
A columnist of the Welt newspaper even questioned whether Kohl
himself had instructed Waigel to speak out.
</P>
<P>
According to an Allensbach Institute poll published Wednesday,
Kohl's party continued to trail the SPD in popularity.
</P>
<P>
His Christian Democratic Union (CDU), along with its Bavarian
sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) chaired by Waigel, would
win just 33.4 percent of the vote if elections were held next
Sunday, the poll said. The SPD meanwhile would win 37.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, in office since 1982, has announced his plan to run for
an unprecedented fifth term. The SPD says it will not choose its
challenger to Kohl until early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
