<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Streamline Air Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, a military power in west
Africa, is to re-appraise its air defense system in a bid to map
out strategies for its sustainable growth and development.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chief of Air Staff, Air Vice Marshall Nsikak
Eduok, the Air Force needs to be re-appraised and streamlined
because of the changes in the world's strategic environment.
</P>
<P>
The move is underlined by the imperative of a comprehensive
national air defense system, which the Nigerian Air Force has not
been given the prominence it deserved, senior Air Force officers
said.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions imposed by western countries in the past several
years have brought problems to Nigeria's armed forces, which are
suffering from short supplies of spare parts of weapons and
shunned from sophisticated military equipment.
</P>
<P>
The military government has to turn to the East for
assistance. The Chief of Defense Staff, Major-General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, has just concluded a 17-day visit to China and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea to seek military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This was the highest ranking military officer of Nigeria to
visit the two countries in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
