<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Retain Tight Monetary Policy (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dai said the central bank will continue to adhere to a
moderately tight monetary policy and will make appropriate
fine-tunings of macro control.
</P>
<P>
Growth in lending must be reasonably checked and state banks
must strictly control their loan portfolios and effectively
improve cash management, said Dai.
</P>
<P>
In economic restructuring, appropriate loans can be made to
facilitate selected efficient capital construction projects
capable of guaranteeing both principal and interest payments,
according to Dai.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that provisions for bad loans in state-owned
banks should be managed in accordance with relevant rules and
regulations in order to support efforts such as enterprise
mergers, bankruptcies and the reemployment of redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
Dai stressed the need to timely review and improve the credit
policy. While focusing support on state-owned enterprises,
commercial banks should make every effort to reasonably satisfy
the requirements of credit needs of enterprises with different
types of ownership, he said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will introduce various measures to prevent and
mitigate the effects of financial risks and create a favorable
financial environment for smoothly implementing monetary and
credit policies, he said, adding that related measures will
include further intensifying supervision and regulation over
financial institutions; banning illegal financial institutions and
activities; seriously investigating and punishing those
responsible for violations of laws and regulations; and preventing
and cracking down on financial crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Parole 360 Prisoners to Mark Liberation Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government will
release 360 prisoners on parole Friday to mark the Day of National
Liberation from Japanese rule in 1945, the Justice Ministry
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners have already taken two-month training and
orientation courses conducted to help them adapt themselves to a
new life outside the jail, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Among those to be released Friday are nine lifetimers and 35
serving sentences of 10 years or longer.
</P>
<P>
Also included are 95 inmates who have obtained technical
certificates, 12 who have passed college equivalency exams and
other state-run qualification tests and six who have won prizes in
government-held contests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
