<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citibank Expands Operation in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Citibank N.A. of the U.S. has
expanded its operation in Nigeria by opening a branch in the
capital Abuja and raising its share in a local joint venture
bank, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
As a result of an investment of 15.6 million U.S. Dollars,
Citibank increased its share in the Nigerian International Bank
from 40 to 75 percent. The bank was thus renamed Citibank Nigeria
on Tuesday, the report revealed.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony marking the two cases on Tuesday in Abuja, the
Citibank's African Division head Anjum Ikbal said his bank has
become more "enthusiastic about Nigeria because its macro-economy
is better."
</P>
<P>
Besides in Nigeria, he said, slow but steady growth is being
witnessed all over Africa, as countries on the continent have
settled down to improve their economies and the lot of their
people.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that African countries are now doing more
business with one another and that there is a tremendous future
for intra-African trade.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Abuja branch is Citibank's 15th in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Citibank first came to Nigeria in 1975 but was forced to
divest from the west Africa country in 1979 as a result of the
indigenization decree.
</P>
<P>
It returned in 1984 with a 40 percent stake in the Nigerian
International Bank, which is among the 10 best banks in Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
