<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Situation Remains Tight in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Food supply is still very tight
and food prices remain high in the east African region following
the drought hitting the sub-region at the beginning of this year,
a U.N. report has said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) issued the
report at a press conference held here on Wednesday, saying that
the impact of the drought affecting most of east African
countries was still being felt in all the affected countries.
</P>
<P>
The report of "Food Supply Situation and Crop Prospects in
Sub-Saharan Africa" said that the overall food supply situation
in Kenya remained tight with food prices sharply increased.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the areas planted to maize, the staple food for
Kenyans, had fallen short of the target in spite of the
prevailing high prices of maize.
</P>
<P>
The late rains during the long rain season resulted in delayed
planting of maize, it said, adding that the maize output in the
country was estimated above last year's below-normal crop, but
lower than the bumper crop of 1994.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, the report pointed out, the food supply situation
has tightened with prices of beans and maize doubling during the
past year.
</P>
<P>
The situation is particularly difficult in the eastern and
northeastern districts which were affected by drought and floods
while insecurity in northern districts is hampering food
production and distribution, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The food supply situation is still tight in the
drought-affected areas of north, northeast and the coast area of
Tanzania, said the report, adding that these areas appear to be
headed for another poor harvest this year.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the report stated, the 1996/97 cereal production of
Tanzania is forecast to decline by some 18 percent compared with
last year.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, Eritrea, Somalia and Sudan, the outcome of the
main season crops is uncertain as much depends on weather
developments until harvesting in November and December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
