<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Launched on Illegal Direct Selling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration for
Industry and Commerce (SAIC), the watchdog of the government
market, today announced it has launched a national crackdown on
illegal direct selling.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the campaign, to be carried out in August and
September, is to combat the numerous forms of unlawful activities
now running rampant in the country, according to Gan Guoping,
deputy-director-general of SAIC.
</P>
<P>
SAIC has concluded that some companies during their employee
training process have used false advertising to lure people into
direct selling schemes, propagating superstition, involvement in
underworld gangs, and heresy.
</P>
<P>
Other activities include the selling of fake or substandard
products, smuggling commodities or those products prohibited by
State law to be sold, cheating, and making excessively high profit
from direct selling.
</P>
<P>
Government employees, military personnel, full-time students
and other people as named in relevant laws are also prohibited
from engaging in direct marketing sales.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will also clamp down on authorized direct selling
enterprises that are engaged in cross-regional activities or
trading commodities out of their scope of business and
single-level direct selling businesses involved in tiered selling.
</P>
<P>
According to Gan, SAIC branches across the country in the first
half of this year revoked the license of over 200 illegal direct
selling enterprises, dealt with over 1,100 illegal cases, seized
commodities worth over 40 million yuan (4.82 million US dollars),
and collected fines amounting to over 12.6 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Due to immature market conditions, direct selling is being
developed in a restricted and controlled manner," Gan said.
</P>
<P>
SAIC has approved 40 enterprises throughout the country for
multi-level direct selling, including 17 overseas-funded
enterprises now being re-examined by the SAIC, since their
operation qualification was due in April.
</P>
<P>
The organization also will review the qualifications of the
enterprises involved in single-level direct selling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
