<HEADLINE> More Local Institutional Participation Contributes to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today more local institutional
participation would contribute towards reducing excessive
volatility" in the Kuala Lumpur stock Exchange (KLSE).
</P>
<P>
He stressed that more local institutional participation in the
KLSE would balance off a twin problem in the market: volatility
and sudden changes in market direction.
</P>
<P>
"This is not to say that we do not want retail investors in the
market, but there is a need to balance the current proportion
where the market is more retail-based," he said at the Third
Malaysia Capital Growth Opportunities Exposition here today.
</P>
<P>
Local institutional participation could reduce the dominance
foreign funds had in swaying the market to events which were not
directly related to the domestic capital market or economic
conditions, said Anwar, who is also finance minister.
</P>
<P>
"As the capital market in this region grows in tandem with
economic growth, it has to be ensured that the Malaysian market
stands out as a competitive and efficient capital market in this
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
On average, about two-thirds of KLSE's daily trade is retail,
the individual players buying and selling. Institution trade
refers generally to large amounts of shares traded by fund
management companies, foreign and local.  
</P>
</TEXT>
