<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 08:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Build Its Own Defense Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is making efforts to
develop its own defense industry, in a bid to meet strategic
needs of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted reliable defense
sources, whose names were not given, as saying that Turkey should
give priority to domestic defense industry and make the country
capable of selling weapons abroad.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Turkey would lag behind in the next
century's rapidly-growing defense sector unless it speeds up its
efforts in this respect.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Turkey, as a regional
military power, has to import nearly 80 percent of its arms from
Western countries to meet the demands of the Turkish Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
Defense experts hold that Turkey should raise the proportion
of the home-made weapons in its military equipment by expanding
financial input for the domestic defense industry.
</P>
<P>
This could prevent Turkey, which owns the second largest force
in North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), from making
concessions in case an arms embargo is imposed on it, the experts
said.
</P>
<P>
Ankara was greatly angered when the United States suspended
last year the delivery of three frigates ordered by the Turkish
Navy, under strong pressure from anti-Turkish lobbies.
</P>
<P>
Recently the Clinton administration has given signals that it
is willing to go ahead with the deal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is enhancing cooperation in the defense field with
Israel, hoping this would help quicken the pace of development of
its defense industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
