<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Economy Reaches Higher Level (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The sustainable and rapid growth
of China's rural economy over the past five years has guaranteed
the country's grain supply, as well as thriving market and the
overall health of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The total output value of agriculture, forestry, animal
husbandry, and fisheries has maintained an annual average increase
of 8.6 percent since the 14th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) in 1992, according to a recent report
released by the State Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
China record 1996 grain output of 490 million tons, up 12.6
percent on 1991, and much higher than population growth during the
same period. The year's per capita grain output exceeded 400 kg
for the first time to end at 414 kg.
</P>
<P>
Improvements in agriculture have greatly enhanced the State's
confidence to mainly rely on its own efforts and ability to
provide sufficient food for its growing population, according to
the SSB report.
</P>
<P>
The forestry industry enjoyed average growth of seven percent,
with efforts to plant trees on more than 27 million ha greatly
promoting the nationwide afforestation drive.
</P>
<P>
The animal husbandry sector produced 59.15 million tons of meat
in 1996, a rise of 88.1 percent over 1991, with the livestock herd
reaching 166.5 million head by the end of last year, over 6.9
million head more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries have risen by an average 17.4 percent, with last
years aquatics product output of 28.13 million tons doubling the
figure five years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rural Economy Reaches Higher Level (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yet another notable characteristic of rural economic growth
centers on non-agricultural businesses, such as rural industry,
building industry, transportation and service sectors, which have
expanded by leaps and bounds to become the major contributors to
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
China's non-agricultural industries reported an output value of
651.9 million yuan in 1996, a six-fold increase over 1991, and have
emerged as a major channel for increasing rural income levels.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises, the main component of non-agricultural
industries, have also recorded great strides over the past five
years. The accounted for 25.9 percent of the country's 1996 GDP,
with its value-added output making up 44 percent of the national
total.
</P>
<P>
The report further noted that the rural economic structure has
continue to improve, with the proportion of secondary industry and
service sectors accounting for 73.6 percent of total rural supply
and demand. The two sectors currently employ more than 130 million
redundant rural laborers, or nearly 50 percent more than in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report also noted that another eight million members of
the rural labor forces are moving to non-agricultural regions.
</P>
<P>
Booming economic growth has led to marked improvements in the
living standards of rural residents, with the 1996 per capita
income ending at 1,926 yuan, up 31.7 percent on 1991 in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Each 100 rural households now own 139.8 bicycles, 88 television
sets, and 7.3 refrigerators, with said figures representing wide
marging growth for each item.
</P>
<P>
Monumental achievements have also been made in improving the
overall quality of the rural population, promoting agricultural
mechanization and building rural communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Stock Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Component Stock Index on the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange finished at 4,304.95 today, up 134.28
points from the previous session, according to the Guangfa
Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
A Share Index: 4,863.68, up 136.46 points.
</P>
<P>
B Share Index: 1,249.06, up 113.52 points.
</P>
<P>
Total Turnover: 5,135,781,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Total Volume:  412,538,800 shares. 
