<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Service System Established in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China has basically established
its own civil service system within a short four years, Chinese
vice-minister of personnel Zhang Xuezhong said here today.
</P>
<P>
The idea of setting up an efficient civil service system was
first put forth by Chinese President Jiang Zemin, who is also
General-Secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China (CPC), in his report to the 14th CPC National Congress in
1992.
</P>
<P>
On August 14 of the following year, Premier Li Peng signed an
order to enact the "Temporary Regulations on Civil Servants."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here today marking the fourth anniversary
of the promulgation of the temporary regulations, Zhang said that
the civil service system has to date been adopted in all
departments of the State Council, China's central government, and
most local governments at the provincial and prefectural levels.
</P>
<P>
"Transitional work in governments at the county and township
levels is expected to be largely accomplished by the end of this
year," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in recent years, an open and fair recruiting
system, a competitive and vigorous management mechanism, and a
complete and strict legal supervisory system have been gradually
taking shape in China's civil service.
</P>
<P>
The civil service system China is now promoting nationwide
includes a series of specific sub-systems, such as categorization
of posts, recruiting through open exams, annual performance
examination, exchange of posts, withdrawal, and dismissal of
incompetent officials.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these systems have been practiced in most parts of the
country," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since 1994, the central government
departments have for three consecutive years recruited new civil
servants through open exams, and governments of 28 provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions across the country have
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, almost all personnel in China's administrative
bodies at all levels have in recent years undergone performance
reviews, and some 52,000 civil servants exchanged jobs in 1996
alone.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some 5,500 civil servants across the country have
been dismissed for incompetence or other problems during the past
four years, and another 16,000 have been allowed to quit.
</P>
<P>
"We have worked out 36 specific regulations and detailed
stipulations to manage the civil service contingent in accordance
with the temporal regulations," said Zhang, adding that his
ministry is now working on a draft law on civil service.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Minister highly praised the adoption of the civil
service system, which he said has remarkably enhanced the vitality
of government bodies, raised the general quality of the civil
servants, and promoted the building of a clean and efficient
government.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Personnel will make every effort to further
deepen the reform of the existing personnel system and
continuously improve the newly-established civil service system,"
he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0162 </DOCNO>
