<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000 Flee in Western Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 people of western
Uganda have fled their homes to avoid a possible raid from
rebels, ''the New Vision paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Muhongya, the local council chairman of Bugoye
sub-county in kasese district, told the paper that the whole
Katoke parish have been deserted. A parish consisted of several
villages.
</P>
<P>
Residents in neighboring villages confirmed the report, saying
they had admitted their relatives or friends from the parish.
Many displaced people fled without food and some of them
sheltered in churches.
</P>
<P>
Local people saw rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF)
last week. The ADF rebels threatened to launch another raid in
the sub-county. A sub-county includes some parishes.
</P>
<P>
Kasese is the haunt of the rebels of ADF, which at present has
some 300 members.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni pledged to reorganize the
army in the west and send reinforcements of 3,000 troops to the
west to put down the rebellion of the ADF late last month. But
there was no major operation reported in the west since then. A
recent report said the Uganda army has killed 15 ADF rebels in
western Budinbugyo district.
</P>
<P>
The ADF sent a detachment of 50 rebels to Budibugyo, another
western district to collect food in mid June. But the Uganda army
in the district foiled the attempt, killed the commander of the
detachment and drove the remnants of the detachment into Rwenzori
mountain at the Uganda-Congo border.
</P>
<P>
The ADF had some 1,500 fighters last November and its members
have been declined under the attacks mounted by the Uganda army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
