<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Drawn on Lesson from Thai Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Currency volatility in East
Asian countries will prompt China to adhere to a moderately tight
monetary policy and ensure the rational use of foreign funds,
according to Dai Xianglong, governor of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
"The currency crisis in East Asian countries has provided a
very good lesson," said Dai.
</P>
<P>
He also warned against excessive foreign debt, excessively high
foreign liabilities, and a bubble economy resulting from
overheated real estate and stock markets.
</P>
<P>
"The stability of a nation's currency depends on economic
balance, soundness of the national economy, the exchange rate
system and the government's ability to prevent speculation," said
Dai.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China has no problem in balance of payments in
foreign exchange since 64 percent of the foreign capital in the
country comes from direct foreign investment and 80 percent of
foreign debt totaling 120 billion US dollars is in the form of
long-term loans.
</P>
<P>
Dai also said that China will contribute one billion US dollars
to an international package to help Thailand tide over its current
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The support of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and other Asian countries will enable Thailand to
overcome its current difficulties and successfully restructure
its economy."
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor acknowledged that the Renminbi yuan,
China's currency, is now facing pressure for further
appreciation due in part to growing foreign exchange reserves
which reached 126 billion US dollars at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Dai also noted that the central bank is fully capable of
maintaining basic stability of the country's exchange rate,
although changes in market supply and demand for foreign
exchange may affect the exchange rate to some degree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
