<HEADLINE> Malaysia's 1998 Budget to Curb Imports, Expand Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today his country's budget for 1998
will look at serious measures to curb imports and focus on
expanding exports.
</P>
<P>
"The government would take into account "any monetary measures"
including the use of taxes to increase exports and reduce
imports," he said at the opening of the Third Malaysia Capital
Growth Opportunities Exposition here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia recorded a trade deficit of 2.8 billion Ringgit (about
1.07 billion U.S. dollars) for June this year due to the increase
of imports by 23.7 percent year-on-year to 19.3 billion Ringgit
(about 7.42 billion U.S. dollars) with the bulk comprising lumpy
imports.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the current deficit position was only temporary and
that the import of capital goods was necessary in order to avoid
the situation of continuing trade deficits in the future.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's June trade deficit figures were not all that
alarming, Anwar said, adding that the data required further
clarification, especially as to how they were computed.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was following international norms when
computing these data and had no choice but to follow. "That is why
we have to be seen to be tough in handling these issues," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He raised the possibility that the government might defer
non-critical projects to help ease the pressure on the current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget is scheduled to be tabled in Parliament in
October this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
