<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Standardizes Public Property Auctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
recently adopted regulations on public property auctions.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, public property includes
goods confiscated by judicial organs and law enforcement
departments, as well as other public property that needs to be
auctioned.
</P>
<P>
The regulations also allow items abandoned in public places
such as airports, railway stations and ports to be auctioned
following unsuccessful attempts to find owners.
</P>
<P>
Public property auctions should be sponsored by designated
state-run companies, and all necessary procedures must be
completed prior to an auction.
</P>
<P>
Cultural relics and jewelry should be appraised by experts and
auctions must be approved by related departments.
</P>
<P>
Drugs, pornographic material, dangerous articles, counterfeit
items and contraband cannot be auctioned, and related handling
must be carried out in accordance with the law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
