<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Garment Industry Faces EC Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's garment industry, the
biggest foreign currency earner in this South Asian country, is
facing an embarrassing situation as its biggest buyer threatened
to close the huge profitable market.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission (EC) has threatened once again early
this month to withdraw the General System of Preference (GSP)
facility if Dhaka fails to cancel the inaccurate GSP certificates
by October 1.
</P>
<P>
The deadline was set by the commission after the Bangladeshi
government failed to take any measures to cancel 6,910 GSP
certificates which, an EC investigation team found late last year,
were not issued in compliance with the rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's garment industry has been enjoying the GSP
facility in the European Union countries since 1986 without any
quota restrictions. In other words, the exported products of
Bangladesh can enjoy duty-free or low-duty treatment from the
European countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the products must be made of indigenous materials to
get these privileges, which give this country's garment industry
an edge over its competitors.
</P>
<P>
In the case of knitwear, entrepreneurs may import raw materials
like wool and cotton but they must go through three stages like
preparing yarn and fabrics for knitwear products while in woven
garments, only a two-stage transformation should be performed.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Dhaka fetched a total of 763
million U.S. dollars from its exports of knit items in the 1996-97
fiscal year while 605 million dollars or 79 percent of which came
from the European markets.
</P>
<P>
But ready-made garment exports faced a disruption after the EC
investigation team found irregularities in issuing GSP
certificates by the Export Promotion Bureau (EPB) following
complaints that the rules of origin clause are being violated.
</P>
<P>
The EC also required the Bangladesh authorities to carry out an
investigation into some 8,562 "doubtful" GSP certificates, but the
Bangladesh side failed to take any action, thus annoying the EC
further.
</P>
<P>
In a recent letter to the EPB, an EC official informed that the
commission would withdraw the tariff privileges if the conditions
are not met by October 1.
</P>
<P>
However, the Bangladeshi government has yet to decide on this
critical issue because of the apprehension that once it admits
that the forged GSP certificates were issued, this will not only
create an image problem for Bangladesh's exporters but also make
them liable to pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
If Bangladesh cancels the 6,910 GSP certificates, an estimated
28 million dollars would have to be given as an indirect
compensation while the cancellation of the other 8,562 GSP
certificates will cost another 30 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But if Bangladesh refuses to cancel the 6,910 GSP certificates
by October 1, the Customs authorities of the European Union would
ask their respective importers to pay a duty of 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
That would deal a severe blow to the ready-made garment sector,
especially the knitwear exports, as the confidence of the European
buyers in Bangladesh exporters might be eroded.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael Ahmed, who
went to Brussels and tried to find a solution to this dilemma in
January this year, said that he is likely to visit the EC
headquarters again next month.
</P>
<P>
The minister indicated that a decision by the government
regarding the cancellation of the GSP certificates may be delayed
until the end of his proposed visit.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the government will request the EC to
derogate the rules of origin clause of the GSP, as well as to send
another delegation to Dhaka to re-investigate the alleged forged
certificate cases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dhaka will also call for a sympathetic consideration
of Bangladesh's position, mentioning the social implications
likely to be created following a ban on the exports of ready-made
garments to European countries.
</P>
<P>
"The main victims will be the female garment workers because
the ban will lead to closure of at least 100 garment units," said
an official of the Commerce Ministry, adding that some 1.3 million
female employees will lose their jobs due to the ban.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
