<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets Ugandan Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Sino-Ugandan relations have
developed smoothly, especially in the past few years, marked by
constant exchanges of high-level visits and successful cooperation
 in many areas, Chinese Vice-President Rong Yiren said today.
</P>
<P>
Rong made the remark in a meeting with Jotham Tumwesigye,
inspector general of the government of Uganda, and his delegation.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to the delegation, he said that China and
Uganda are developing countries sharing similar historical
experiences.
</P>
<P>
He said that both are concentrating on expanding their
economies, hold the same or similar views on many international
issues, and can step up cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the Chinese economy, Rong said, the
need for effective supervision has become even more important. He
said he hoped that supervisory departments in the two countries
can learn from each other by increasing exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Rong also briefed the delegation on China's domestic situation.
</P>
<P>
Tumwesigye said that since Uganda achieved independence in
1962, Uganda-China relations have developed steadily and the
friendship between the two governments and their peoples has grown
stronger, forming a bilateral relationship that has been good for
each side.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this is his fourth visit to China, and he has
noticed great changes that have taken place in China. He wished
China prosperity and the Chinese people happiness.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is visiting at the invitation of China's
Ministry of Supervision.  
