commanding Harare District Munyaradzi Musariri, were assaulted.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants for Zimbabwe's independence also smashed a
police video camera and a camera of a "Herald" photographer whom
they threatened to assault and also burned his car.
</P>
<P>
They stormed ZANU (PF) headquarters just before lunch and cut
telephone lines at the reception area. Some went downstairs where
they looted food and cigarettes from the canteen.
</P>
<P>
After the looting, the ex-combatants assembled outside the
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Acting Police Commissioner Godwin Matanga has reportedly
instructed his officers to arrest the ex-fighters to face charges
of malicious damage to property. No arrests had been made by
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is dangerous. We also have lives to protect," a
senior officer said at the site at that time.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, at least a hundred ex-fighters held a demonstration
to disrupt the Heroes Day celebration at Heroes Acre in Harare.
</P>
