<HEADLINE> Dry Season Sees Sharp Rise in Veld Fires in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Numerous veld fires have been
reported in Zimbabwe since the beginning of the current dry
season, with incidents in Harare shooting up from a normal 10
fires in a month to 89.
</P>
<P>
This increase was due mainly to the dry season and the school
holidays, during which some school children are believed to be
going around starting fires.
</P>
<P>
Harare Fire Brigade's Divisional Fire Officer Erasmus Gudza
said on Wednesday that the dry season was always characterized by
a sharp rise in veld fires.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the incidents in Harare have risen from a normal 10
in a month to 89 incidents during the same period."
</P>
<P>
"What is most disturbing is that most of these veld fires
developed into house or factory fires, particularly in cases
where proper fire guards are not in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed school children for causing most of the fires. Some
of the fires took long to be put out, as they would be fanned by
strong winds.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to parents to ensure that their children did not
start fires, as some of the fires ended up destroying property.
</P>
</TEXT>
