<HEADLINE> West Urged to End Bias Against Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- President Daniel arap Moi has
called on western countries to end political bias against Kenya
which is facing the general election this year, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some western countries and donor agencies have tended to
support the Opposition at the expense of the political and
economic achievements of the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) party, he charged in western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He said on Wednesday that the introduction of multi-party
system in the east African country had brought with it strong
tribal feelings which, fuelled by the Opposition, culminated in
the clashes that characterized events in the run-up to the last
elections in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret over the suspension of 215-million-Dollar
aid package to Kenya late last month by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) which cited high-level in Kenya as a key
reason.
</P>
<P>
Corruption is a vice rampant world-wide and could not be
identified with Kenya alone, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The conditions being pegged on aid by the IMF were not based
on economic considerations but were political decisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed the government's commitment to both
political and economic reforms, saying it would not backtrack on
the reforms. 
</P>
