<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highway Construction Booming in Hebei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- People driving through
Hebei Province are enjoying a smooth ride these days, owing to a
massive highway construction plan that began five years ago.
</P>
<P>
"While in the past it sometimes took a whole day to cover a
hundred kilometers on narrow and rugged roads, we no longer have
to worry about the road conditions and can travel more quickly,"
said Shang Yuhe, a long-time driver.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Hebei in north China has built ordinary new roads
totalling 6,682 kilometers, and 8,299 kilometers of high-grade
highways, bringing the total length of its roadways to 54,146
kilometers by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Also at the end of 1996, the province had 359 kilometers of
expressways, the fifth-highest amount in the country. The new
roads link Beijing and Shijiazhuang; Beijing, Tianjin and
Tangshan; Shijiazhuang and Taiyuan; and Tangshan and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Hebei also had 261 kilometers of first-grade roads, ranking
eighth in the country; and 1,411 kilometers of second-grade
special motor vehicle roads, ranking first.
</P>
<P>
The province has an ambitious plan for the future, which calls
for the construction of eight expressways before the end of this
century designed to form a high-grade highway network with Beijing
as the center and Tianjin and Shijiazhuang as hubs. This system
will provide access to the province's four major sea ports of
Tianjin, Jingtang, Qinhuangdao, and Huangye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
