<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Increase Income in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- More than a third of farm
families living in south China's Guangdong Province earn 3,400
yuan (400 US dollars) on average annually.
</P>
<P>
The state says that income is the country's standard for a
comfortable living for families in the countryside, meaning having
sufficient food and clothing, and being able to afford some luxury
goods like color TVs and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that farmers' average income has increased
in the province in the past few years, with the number of poor
families (per capita annual income of less than 845 yuan)
declining to 0.7 percent of the total number of families.
</P>
<P>
A recent local government study also shows that the average
annual income of farmers in Guangdong last year was 3,183 yuan, up
17.9 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the Pearl River Delta seem to be much better off
than their cousins in other places, with an average annual income
of 4,267 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that the income gap among the farmers has been
narrowed somewhat because of rapid development and higher
profits. Most farmers' income comes from farming, with money
earned from work in township enterprises accounting for a quarter
of their total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Financial Co-operation with Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Financiers said Guangzhou, the
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, expects to increase
co-operation with Hong Kong in the finance sector.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong province, a neighbor of Hong Kong, is the country's
economic powerhouse, and has more Hong Kong investment than most
other provinces.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is a door for Hong Kong investors to reach interior
provinces, with their cheap labor and natural resources, and the
two should co-operate in finances for mutual benefits, according
to experts.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou will depend on investors from overseas to make up 40
percent of the funds needed for its economy, topping 7.3 billion
US dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's banks and financial institutions were among the
first to enter Guangdong after it opened its financial sector to
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Partially owing to cash inflows via these banks and financial
institutions, Guangzhou has been able to complete massive
construction and infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local commercial banks have opened offices in Hong
Kong. Co-operation between Guangzhou and Hong Kong will help
develop the economy of south China as well, and the effects will
reach interior provinces as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
