<HEADLINE> Caniggia Resigns with Boca Juniors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 13 (Xinhua) -- After a hiatus of one whole
year, former Argentine international Claudio Caniggia made his
comeback by resigning with his old club Boca Juniors on Wednesday
for a one-year-and-six-month contract.
</P>
<P>
Apart from assuring 40,000 US dollars per match into his
pockets, the contract also stipulated that Caniggia was free to go
after next January as long as Boca's requirements are satisfied.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old striker had been linked with several European
clubs after his farewell to Boca Juniors last August, but all fell
through.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, Caniggia said he had never thought of
leaving professional football though he had stayed out for one
year.
</P>
<P>
He hoped to make his return debut on August 24 when the
Argentine National League kicks off.
</P>
<P>
The contract means the resurrection of the Maradona-Caniggia
partnership which awarded Argentina a silver medal in the 1990
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The volatile Argentine superstar Diego Maradona this year made
his fifth comeback to the professional field as Boca Juniors
recruited him at the expense of 50,000 US dollars for every league
match. 
</P>
</TEXT>
