<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Becomes Flower Export Center of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province has become the heart of the country's flower exporting
business, registering a 100 percent annual growth rate of fresh
flowers since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The province produced 400 million fresh flowers last year,
occupied 40 percent of the domestic market, and turned out more
than four million US dollars in export volume.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, which is located in an area with low latitude and high
above sea level, has a range of different climates -- tropical,
temperate and frigid -- and can grow a variety of flowers.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years, many developed countries with superior
natural conditions have become the world's major flower suppliers,
said deputy governor of the province Liu Jing.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, which is seeking international status on the flower
market, has set a series of preferential policies for the
development of its flower industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province has finalized a long-term cooperative deal with
Israel, the world's fourth largest flower exporter, to introduce
advanced techniques and equipment for flower production.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than a dozen overseas flower companies from the
Netherlands, the United States, Israel, Japan and the Republic of
Korea as well as companies from Hong Kong and Taiwan have invested
in the province, he said.
</P>
<P>
The seed cultivation centers for tulips and lilies were built
in northwest Yunnan and the largest flower market in southwest
China was built in the province's capital city of Kunming.
</P>
<P>
The production of tropical plants and flowers developed quickly
in the southern part of the province, with more than three million
tropical orchids grown each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 06:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Wraps Up Shuttle Mission With Limited Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 14 (Xinhua) -- United States special envoy
Dennis Ross concluded his four-day shuttle mission overnight
with a limited success in restoring the Israeli-Palestinian
security relationship.
</P>
<P>
Before returning to Washington, Ross held the final and fifth
meeting Wednesday night with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat in Ramallah, West Bank. Before the
meeting, Ross already conferred with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in his car on the way from Tel Aviv's
Ben-Gurion Airport to Jerusalem, when the latter returned from a
visit to Jordan's Aqaba to meet with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Summarizing his mission to reporters after meeting Arafat,
Ross said his trip was aimed at affecting the security relations
between Israel and the PNA in order to prevent the situation from
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
He said he had succeeded in creating a mechanism to
reestablish the Israeli-Palestinian security ties. "We certainly,
at this point, have a beginning which makes it possible to do
what is essential - settle the political differences," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ross was apparently referring to the two heigh-level meetings
between Israeli and Palestinian security officials arranged by
him and supervised by the station chief of the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency based in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
He also believed that Israel would ease some of the sanctions
imposed against the Palestinians following the twin suicide
bombings in Jerusalem's Manahe Yehuda market on July 30,
including the total closure on West Bank and the Gaza Strip, and
halt of transfer of tax money. But he did not elaborate when
Israel would do so.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel and the PNA had different interpretations of
Ross' self-claimed success.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman David Bar-Illan said Israel gave Ross
credit for succeeding in setting up the security ties and
influencing the PNA to take security seriously, but it had yet to
see "any concrete actions" by the PNA to stamp out terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On its part, the PNA was less positive in their assessment of
Ross' mission. Senior Palestinian negotiator Nabil Shaath said
that Ross came "empty-handed" to meet Arafat overnight in
Ramallah because he had failed to persuade Israel to ease the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Former Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat praised Ross
for having "managed to put damage control mechanisms into effect
and stop the deterioration."
</P>
<P>
But he also expressed regret that Ross failed to obtain any
concessions from Israel to ease the anti-Palestinian sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Due to his success in restoring the Israeli-Palestinian
security ties, Ross said that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright would be sure to visit the region for the first time in
the near future. Erekat agreed that "the road is open for a
visit by Albright" to get the peace process rolling again.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, the speculation is that Albright is likely to
visit Middle East in the first week of September and that Ross
will return before then to prepare for her much-expected
trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
