<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Scheme for Girl Child to Be Launched in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral is set to announce a unique scheme for the girl child on
the golden jubilee of independence of India on August 15, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The union government will open a separate bank account for
every girl born in the country, putting in 5,000 rupees ( about
140.85 U.S. dollars) as the initial capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, the money put in the bank will grow as
the child grows and by the time she becomes old enough to join
school, the corpus will generate enough monthly interest to
support her necessities. The scheme is particularly aimed at
promoting female literacy, checking the comparative disadvantages
suffered by a girl child in the family and, most importantly,
prevent female infanticide and foeticide.
</P>
<P>
In the man-dominated society of India, the social status of
women is very low, not to say the girl child. The new scheme for
the girl child will be the second major step taken by the Gujral
government to improve women' status in the country after expansion
of the council of ministers to induct only four women ministers
early this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Wheat Hybrids Likely to Pierce Yield Barrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have expressed the
hope to come out with wheat hybrids in the next few years to break
the present yield barrier.
</P>
<P>
Top wheat scientists from India and abroad, who are
participating in a three-day international meet in India on wheat
research needs of the next century, said that hybrid and
transgenic wheat is now a distinct possibility. They are
attempting to transfer genes from other plants into wheat to
change the physiological and genetic nature of the wheat plant.
</P>
<P>
They said that the evolution of genetically superior plants,
coupled with the improvement in cultivation practices, will help
ensure a steady increase in wheat productivity.
</P>
<P>
S. Rajaram, successor of Nobel Laureate Norman E. Borlaug as
the head of the wheat breeding program at the Mexico-based
International Wheat and Maize Research Institute said at the
meeting Wednesday that scientists are now quite close to producing
a new type of wheat plant which will have a better root system,
stem and leaf architecture and grain-bearing ears. The new
"robust plant" could have a far superior yield potential than the
types available at present.
</P>
<P>
Indian wheat breeders also seem enthusiastic about the
prospects of hybrid wheat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
