<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB helps Bangladesh to Mitigate Arsenic Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB), in
association with the Bangladeshi government and other donor
agencies, is going to launch a package program to mitigate arsenic
contamination problem of drinking water in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The program, named "Umbrella investment project", is expected
to cost a total of 50 million U.S. dollars, according to World
Bank sources.
</P>
<P>
Twenty million dollars would be available from the
International Development Association, the WB's soft-loan window
for the investment project, 20 million dollars from other
co-financiers and the rest 10 million dollars from the Bangladeshi
government.
</P>
<P>
Water treatment facilities would be developed and alternative
options for supply of arsenic free water would be provided to the
affected people under the umbrella investment project.
</P>
<P>
The package also includes an emergency programs of 0.3 million
dollars funded by the United Nations to provide immediate relief
to the people of 200 most affected villages covering 50 counties
of this natural disaster-prone country.
</P>
<P>
WB officials said that the contamination of ground water by
arsenic has been reported in West Bengal of India since 1983 while
Bangladesh first detected the arsenic problem in 1993.
</P>
<P>
A survey report on water samples collected from 28 out 34
suspected arsenic affected northwestern districts of Bangladesh
reveals an alarming trend with 44.5 percent crossing the maximum
permissible limit of 0.05 mg per liter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 05:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Sends Message on Golan to Assad: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has reportedly sent a secret message Syrian
President Hafez Al-Assad three week ago on renewing talks on the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
According to the Israel Radio today, in the message conveyed by
an anonymous envoy, Netanyahu said Israeli concessions on the
occupied Golan depend on the security arrangements it gets from
Syria.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that Netanyahu expressed his
willingness to make concessions on the issue of Golan Heights
Israel occupied in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak denied the report
today, stating that there is no change in Israel's position
regarding the peace talks with Syria: Israel is still insisting on
a return to the negotiations without prior conditions.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak has also sent a
message to Assad, commending him on inviting an Israeli Arab
delegation to visit Damascus this week and calling on the Syrian
leader to renew peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak criticized the new Golan formula attributed to
Netanyahu, terming it "a major political mistake." He said the
concessions on Golan Heights should only be dependent on the depth
of peace instead of security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Coalition members criticized Barak for sending a message to
Assad with the Israeli-Arab delegates, who have angered Israeli
rightist camp by calling for the return of all Palestinian
refugees to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Likud's lawmaker Michael Kleiner said Barak made a mistake by,
and would pay a price for, using Arab delegates, "traitors" as he
called, as messengers.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction, Barak said he only called on Assad to renew
direct negotiations with Israel, so he did not need anyone's
permission to do so. He denied he had called for the return of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
In Damascus, Assad on Tuesday told the visiting delegation of
Israeli-Arabs that he desires true peace with Israel. He said he
did not want war and did not foresee deterioration.
</P>
<P>
The 44-member delegation started an eight-day visit to Syria
early this week in a bid to ease the tension between the two
countries and find a way to renew negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been frozen since March last
year and tensions have been growing since the hardline Likud
government came to power in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite repeated Israeli call for resumption of talks without
any conditions, Syria insists that Israel should promise first to
the full withdrawal from the occupied Golan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
