<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 05:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Posting Anti-Islamic Leaflets to Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Tatiana Susskind, who posted
anti-Islamic leaflets in Hebron, West Bank, will soon stand trial
after a court ruled today that she is mentally sane.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem District Court ruled today that Susskind, 26,
from Jerusalem, is mentally fit to stand trial. This ruling
rejected her lawyer's appeal that she was mentally unstable and
not fit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
Susskind was arrested late June after posting some leaflets
in the flash point West Bank city of Hebron, which depicted the
Islamic prophet Mohammed as a pig writing on the holy Koran.
</P>
<P>
The leaflets triggered angry protests from Palestinians as
well as Muslim across the world, and led to a wave of
anti-Israeli violence in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Susskind was indicted on July 3 in the Jerusalem District
Court with charges of offending religious sensibilities, throwing
rocks at Arab cars and supporting Jewish terror group.
</P>
<P>
When she posted the offensive leaflets in Hebron, Susskind
was wearing a shirt with the clenched fist symbol of the
outlawed extremist Kach Movement. One day before her arrest, she
threw stones at passing Arab cars on the road linking Hebron and
the nearby Jewish settlement Kiryat Arba.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Supreme Court postponed the opening session of
Susskind's trial because of her lawyer's appeal against the
indictment citing her mental problems.
</P>
<P>
Following today's court ruling, Susskind's trial is expected
to begin soon. If convicted, Susskind could be sentenced for a
maximum of 20 years for endangering life on roads, in addition to
one year for offending religious sensibilities and another two
years for supporting terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
