<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Gets Large Amount of Aid for Restruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has received 480
million U.S. dollars in grants and loans for the restruction of
the country since October last year, according to an official
report published today.
</P>
<P>
This brings the total available funding to 3.6 billion
dollars since the 10-year restruction program launched in 1993
shortly after Prime Minister Rafik Al-Hariri came to power.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was conducted by Lebanon's Council of
Restruction and Development, said the European Union and the
European Investment Bank have provided most of the financing
generated in the last eight months, with a total of 226 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other recent loans have come from the Arab Fund for Economic
and Social Development and the Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic
Development.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the World Bank has allocated a loan of
47 million dollars for the coastal wastewater project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Police Focus on Improving Traffic Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Polish police have taken
steps to reduce the number of road accidents occurring in the
country and improve traffic safety.
</P>
<P>
An excessive number of traffic accidents from January to July
this year has resulted in an obvious increase in fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents in the first seven months of this year rose
22.7 percent over that of the same period last year, with
casualties increasing 22.6 percent and the death toll climbing by
26 percent, the Polish General Office of Police reported.
</P>
<P>
In July 1997, road accidents numbered 6,550, up 18 percent over
the same month in 1996. The number of casualties in the month
totalled 8,600 and fatalities numbered 477.
</P>
<P>
The Polish police attribute the occurrence of accidents to a
range of factors such as drunk driving, falling asleep at the
steering wheel while driving, fast driving, driving without
wearing safety belts or helmets as well as violations of traffic
regulations on the part of pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a nationwide traffic safety campaign is being staged
in Poland. The police have taken measures to heighten inspections
of vehicles and supervision over pedestrians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Cut Vehicle Pollution in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Romania will make an all-out
effort to cut vehicle emissions and ease pollution problems within
the next five years, Transport Minister Traian Basescu announced
here today.
</P>
<P>
Basescu said that vehicles being made in Romania must reach
antipollution standards by January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 3.2 million vehicles in Romania, one
third of which have not reached antipollution standards. He said
the Romanian government will soon pass a decree that will set
pollution standards and emission levels for newly manufactured
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of vehicles that exceed the standard for auto
exhaust emission levels and continue to pollute the environment
will be fined, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that beginning in 1998, Romania will
demand that the European Transport Ministry Council limit
international long-distance transport vehicles that do not meet
vehicle-emission standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
