<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Central Bank Governor on Interest Rates, Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China's interest rate level for
bank deposits and loans is currently faily reasonable, said Dai
Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Dai said here this morning that
China's actual interest rates for bank deposits after adjusted for
inflation are at the same level of those in most Western countries.
</P>
<P>
"The actual interest rates for the present are in favor of the
interests of depositors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor also acknowledged that the Chinese
currency, the Renminbi yuan, is now under pressure for further
appreciation, partly due to growing foreign exchange reserves,
which reached 126 billion US dollars by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the market change in the supply and demand of
foreign exchange will not affect the exchange rate much, since the
country's foreign exchange system, though market-oriented, is well
under the administration of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
From the perspective of foreign exchange management, the
central bank hopes to keep the exchange rate stable, Dai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
