<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TA Device to Keep Buildings Cool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Industry watchers say that
although most buildings in China look luxurious from the outside,
they lack a balanced heating or air conditioning system.
</P>
<P>
TA Hydronics from Sweden is seeking to solve this syndrome in
Chinese buildings, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
TA, a Swedish company owned by IMI of Britain, sells balancing
valves, which distribute the flow of water correctly in hydronic
systems.
</P>
<P>
Apartments without balancing valves are often too cold if they
are farther from the boiler and too warm if closer. But if you
insert resistances in the piping, the heating system is balanced.
</P>
<P>
"We are having a stronger focus on China," Jeff Clarke, TA
manager for Asia/Australia, said on his first trip to Beijing last
week.
</P>
<P>
TA balancing products and formulas first came to China in 1983,
but sales have been low because China has yet to pay attention to
the comfort of buildings, explained T.S. Lim, TA regional sales
manager.
</P>
<P>
China's building market has been booming in recent years after
ups and downs in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Clarke said TA would first target high-grade commercial and
government buildings in Beijing and Shanghai. Then a variety of
valves will be available for buildings of other types.
</P>
<P>
TA (Tour &AMP; Andersson) was the first in the world to invent
modern balancing valves in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Clarke did not say for sure TA would invest in China to help
bring down production costs, but said local investment "is
something we are looking at seriously." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
