<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0230 GMT, August 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- A team of astronomers from the United States and
Germany has discovered trace amounts of hydrogen fluoride gas in
the near vacuum of interstellar space, the European Space Agency
said Wednesday. Although approximately 100 different kinds of
molecules have been detected in interstellar space over the past
30 years, the discovery of hydrogen fluoride is the first time
that a molecule containing fluorine has been detected in an
interstellar gas cloud, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British Ministry of Defense is considering to use
synthetic alternatives to replace the honor guards' bearskin hats
made from the Canadian brown bearskin.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister for defense procurement John Gilbert has urged
the army to look at synthetic replacements for the present
headgear, known as the busby. However, synthetic fake fur could
prove to be a disaster. An army spokesman said, "When the
(synthetic) hats are dry, they attract a great deal of static
electricity."
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The food supply situation in Sierra Leone has
deteriorated and, famine is imminent if the present insecurity
persists, according to a report released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Tajik Deputy Interior Minister Abdusattor Radzhabov
and the commander of a rapid reaction brigade, Colonel Sukhrob
Kasymov, denied Wednesday that armed clashes were continuing in
Kurgan Tyube and the Gisar valley as some reports said.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Talks between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Jordan's King Hussein on Wednesday appeared short of
softening Israel's stance in the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Wednesday that the United States would likely choose Argentina as
its close military ally outside the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"This status is open to other countries, including Chile,"
Albright said at a news conference with visiting Chilean Foreign
Minister Jose Miguel Insulza.
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Two makeshift bombs exploded on the Greek island of
Crete Wednesday morning, destroying two cars, but injuring no
one. According to the semi-official Athens News Agency, the cars
belonged to the deputy mayor of Keramies, Iosif Sarikakis. No one
has claimed responsibility for the explosions.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A new kind of altitude warning system could
prevent aircraft from crashing into mountains and the United
States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) may require all
airliners to install such equipment, The New York Times reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's Ontario Hydro announced Wednesday that it
will temporarily shutdown seven of its nuclear reactors in a major
overhaul of its production facilities. The board of directors at
North America's largest power utility approved the overhaul in
response to an extensive evaluation of its nuclear assets
conducted during the past few months. The evaluation report, which
prompted Hydro president Allan Kupcis to resign Tuesday, gives the
utility barely a passing grade on safety but says it's still at an
acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- With little more than one month remaining before
Norway's parliamentary election on September 15, opinion polls are
predicting that the ruling Labor Party will lose ground, while the
far-right Progress Party may be the big winner, according to a
press report here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- A new species of monkey, the smallest in the
world with the size of a mouse, has been discovered in the Amazon
region in Brazil, the local media reported Wednesday. Danish
biologist Mark Van Roosmalen, who spotted such monkeys 11 years
ago when working in the region, captured one last April. The
monkeys, weighing between 160 and 200 grams, live in groups of 30
in an area of about 3 million hectares in the Amazon region,
Roosmalen was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
