<HEADLINE> Xiamen Investment Helps Boeing Diversify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Boeing, US-Based airplane
manufacturer, has bought a stake in an Asian company that offers
aircraft maintenance and modification services in China, a move
that strengthens its foothold in China and broadening its
diversification internationally.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 11 million US dollars, "China Daily"
reported today, Boeing became a 9.1-percent owner of the Taikoo
(Xiamen) Aircraft Engineering Co Ltd (TAECO), an aircraft
heavy-maintenance center based in Xiamen, Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The TAECO maintenance facility, operated for 18 months, is
managed by the Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering Co Ltd, its largest
shareholder, and specializes in 747, 737 and 757 maintenance,
repair and overhaul services, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing said the joint venture will expand its aircraft heavy-
maintenance and modification business and strengthen links with
several Boeing customers.
</P>
<P>
The partnership will give the TAECO the opportunity to have an
annual capability of modifying up to three older 747s from
passenger configurations to all-cargo freighter layouts, which
will also increase Boeing's current modification capacity.
</P>
</TEXT>
