<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian PM Shows Confidence in New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's new cabinet is an
organized working group with great potentialities to carry out
reform in the country, Ukrainian Prime Minister Valeriy
Pustovoitenko said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to state the government's future
policies and tasks, Pustovoitenko showed great confidence in his
new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministers are all experienced and professional
people, and they have the same goal and cherish a collective
spirit.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko, 50, was named prime minister on July 16, the
seventh in Ukraine's six-year independence.
</P>
<P>
In less than one month, Pustovoitenko formed his new government
following the principle of efficient and simple administration. He
cut the government ministries from 27 to 21, and set up 23 special
commissions.
</P>
<P>
Talking about national economy, Pustovoitenko admitted that
Ukraine's economic situation at present is quite complicated, but
promised that his government would shoulder all the
responsibilities to restore economy.
</P>
<P>
As for specific measures, Pustovoitenko said that his
government would first pay the back salaries and pensions.
</P>
<P>
It would also take comprehensive measures to control financial
crisis, adopt new budget policy and start economic structural
reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that to promote the development of small and
medium-sized enterprises as well as high-tech industries is also
one of the highlights of his economic policy.
</P>
<P>
All of Pustovoitenko's six predecessors have failed to bring
Ukraine out of the downward economic spiral since the former
Soviet republic gained independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said Pustovoitenko and his cabinet raised new
hope for the Ukrainian people but it would take time to help the
country get rid of economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
