<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Adhere to Moderately Tight Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank will adhere
to a moderately tight monetary policy and at the same time make
appropriate fine-tunings of macro control, Dai Xianglong, governor
of the People's Bank of China, said at a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
First of all lending growth must be reasonably checked and
state banks strictly bring their loan portfolio under control and
effectively improve cash management, Dai noted.
</P>
<P>
He also said that more efforts must be made to restructure the
economy.
</P>
<P>
For some efficient capital construction projects which can
guarantee payments for principals and interests, he added,
Renminbi yuan loan facilities could be appropriately extended.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that provisions for bad loans in the
state-owned banks should be well managed in accordance with
relevant rules and regulations in order to support efforts in
enterprise merger, bankruptcy and re-employment of the lay-offs.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he stressed the need to timely review and improve the
credit policy, saying that while focusing support on the
state-owned enterprises the commercial banks should also
reasonably satisfy requirements of credit funds from enterprises
with different types of ownership.
</P>
<P>
To prevent and mitigate the effects of financial risks and to
create a favorable financial environment for smoothly implementing
the monetary and credit policy, the central bank will further
intensify supervision and regulation over the financial
institutions, ban illegal financial institutions and activities,
seriously probe into and punish operations in violation of laws
and regulation, and prevent and crack down on financial criminal
activities, the governor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
