<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices Cut as Retailers Chase Summer Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Major retailers in China are now
embroiled in a price-cutting campaign to promote sales marked by
low inflation and improved after-sales service, today's "China
Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
State Statistics Bureau (SSB) economists noted that retail
prices went down from June to July in China, but this drop did not
have a great influence on the buying mood of Chinese consumers as
they became more choosy.
</P>
<P>
The supply of some consumer goods exceeded demand in some areas
of the country. Grain prices in the 36 major cities went down 1.6
percent on average last month due to a bumper cereal harvest this
summer. The retail prices of garments, cloth, household
appliances, transportation and telecommunications were on a
downward trend.
</P>
<P>
However, there was also some bad news for Chinese urban
residents. The retail prices of drinking water, electricity and
fuels went up by 1.4 percent on average in the major cities from
June to July. SSB also noted that it was more expensive to travel
by air last month.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, retail and consumer prices racked up
increases of 0.9 percent and 3.5 percent respectively in July in
the 36 major cities, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
