<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Munitions Trade Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's munitions
trade in 1996 declined by one third of the previous year's to some
150 million U.S. dollars, a report of the Industry and Trade
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, exports dropped by 24 percent to 120 million
dollars, and imports to 34.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance has moved the country from the world's 7th
largest munitions trade power in the late 1980s to the 14th
nowadays, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic enjoys a long history of munitions
export. During the First World War in 1914-18, it became one of
the world largest producers and exporters of arms and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
And in the two world wars, its munitions exports reportedly
occupied 40 percent of the total world munitions trade.
</P>
<P>
The munitions industry had at times accounted for 30-50 percent
of the country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic's flourish munitions industry plummeted
after the 1989 tremendous change in the country, with the new
leadership asserting that it was not to be arms dealer any more.
</P>
<P>
However, in 1993, the leadership changed its mind and said the
country should regain its reputation of a munitions power by
recapturing its lost world market share.
</P>
<P>
Following that, the country's 40 major factories and
enterprises joined efforts to form a manufacturing group that has
greatly boosted Czech munitions output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
