<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Help Small-Fund Property Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will
continue to fund the country's ailing property sector, but this
time only for those projects involving funds less than 2 million
baht (67,000 U.S. dollars) or 80 percent completed.
</P>
<P>
The policy was stressed at a special committee meeting convened
to solve the problems in the property sector on Wednesday, local
newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The government would assist the low-income and mass-housing
projects instead of luxury ones, Minister of the Prime Minister's
Office Bokhin Polakula said.
</P>
<P>
The government would not be able to help all projects, but only
those targeting low-income earners and at least 80 percent
completed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The representatives from property associations who attended the
meeting were urged to present accurate information about their
projects to the related committees for review before the total
amount for the projects is set on August 25.
</P>
<P>
Bokhin also said that some of the International Monetary Fund's
aid to Thailand may be helpful for the property sector, but only
to those designated projects.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Thai Finance Ministry is also
considering to cut the three-percent special tax on land
transactions to ease the tax burden on property developers.
</P>
</TEXT>
