<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor Says China's Base Money of Central Bank Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the People's Bank of
China, Dai Xianglong, said today that the base money of the
central bank has been well under control and the money market
transaction has been steady this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Dai said that base money, a
major indicator of the money supply, came to 2,750 billion yuan at
the end of July, an increase of 18.8 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the increase of foreign exchange holdings
resulted in an additional 175.4 billion yuan of liquidity, which
was 33.5 billion yuan more than in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, the central bank
recalled 107 billion yuan of loans from financial institutions,
which was 63.7 billion yuan more than in the same 1996 period, Dai
said.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the ratio of standby liquidity of
commercial banks was 7.7 percent at the end of July, a rate he
said indicates that banks are well equipped with sufficient
payment capability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
