<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New And Better Rare Fish for Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Fishermen in China's northernmost
Heilongjiang Province have shown some interest in salangid (or
whitebait), a variety of fish that is expected to earn foreign
currency for them.
</P>
<P>
This year they hope to get more than 100,000 tons of the fish
from the province's 65,000 hectares of fisheries, officials there
said.
</P>
<P>
The salangid, which is native to China, likes living in large
bodies of water at a temperature of from 2 to 6 degrees Celsius,
and grows to an average length of 11 to 19 centimeters. China
often exports the fish to Japan and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang province has good conditions for raising the fish,
and began breeding and doing researches on them in 1995. Central
China's Henan Province has provided the fish eggs, a traditional
product.
</P>
<P>
After two years of experiments, Heilongjiang began breeding
them on a large scale this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Money Supply Grows Appropriately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The money supply in China has
increased appropriately this year, central bank governor Dai
Xianglong said at a news briefing today.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the growth of broad money, known as M2, rose by
34.4 percent in 1994 and dropped to 25.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July this year, he added, the value of M2 stood
at some 8,345 billion yuan, an increase of 18.1 percent
year-on-year, which was 7.2 percentage points lower than that at
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of narrow money, or M1, was some 3,110 billion yuan
by the end of last month, up 18.4 percent from a year ago, or
equal to that of the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Currency in circulation fell to 10.9 percent of M2 at the end
of June, down from 19.8 percent in 1994, Dai said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
