<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three World Records Smashed in Zurich Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Three world records were broken
on a single day of Wednesday at the Zurich Grand Prix, including
the oldest mark in track and field.
</P>
<P>
Danish Wilson Kipketer, a former Kenyan national, had his dream
come true by smashing Briton Sebastian Coe's 16-year-old record in
the 800 meters with a winning time of one minute 41:24.
</P>
<P>
The Dane once tied Coe's 1981 mark of 1:41.73 earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Wilson Boit Kipketer also had his glory moment by beating
the 3,000-meter steeplechase record in 7:59.08. The previous mark
of 7:59.18 was set by fellow Kenyan Moses Kiptanui in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia broke his own 5,000 record in 12
minutes 41.86 seconds, a big stride from his 1995 mark of 12:44.39.
</P>
<P>
Both Kipketers, winners in the World Championship in Athens
last week, were awarded 50,000 US dollars and a kilo of gold as a
bonus for their record-smashing feats.
</P>
<P>
The star-studded Grand Prix depicted a clear contrast against
the World Athletics Championships wherein no single world record
was broken in its nine-day competitions.
</P>
<P>
World champion Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco was only a step
away from setting the fourth record in the 1,500 meters.
</P>
<P>
He clocked the year's fastest time of three minutes 28.91
seconds, which ranked the second best only next to the 1995 world
record of 3:28.91 set by Nourredine Morceli of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Fermin Cacho of Spain, the Olympic and world championship
silver medalist, finished second with a European record of 3:28.95.
</P>
<P>
Frankie Fredericks of Namibia and Merlene Ottey of Jamaica won
the 100 meter dashes, gaining some revenge for their disappointing
performances in Athens.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old Ottey clocked her winning time of 10.96 seconds
to justify her world-class caliber. Ottey finished a miserable
seventh in Athens, beat all the three medalists in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
Noah Ngeny of Kenya posted a junior world record in the 1,500
meters by clocking three minutes 34.54 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Tagged as the biggest meet in the world, the Zurich meet drew
67 medalists from Athens, including 25 champions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trade in Chemicals, Chemical Products Double in Six Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- World trade in chemicals and
chemical products amounted to some 458 billion U.S. dollars in
1995, accounting roughly for 10 percent of the world's total
trade, according to the United Nations Economic Commission for
Europe (UN/ECE).
</P>
<P>
The value is double that of six years earlier, from around 230
billion U.S. dollars in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Western Europe accounts for more than half of world imports of
chemicals and nearly two thirds of world exports.
</P>
<P>
Chemical trade contributes some 30 billion U.S. dollars to the
western European trade balance, while generating a
46-billion-U.S.-dollar trade deficit in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In North America, Canada's imports of chemicals and related
products in 1995 amounted to 13 billion U.S. dollars and its
exports to 11 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The chemical imports of the United States in the same year were
42 billion U.S. dollars and its exports 60.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, Japan imported 24 billion U.S. dollars worth of
chemicals and related products in 1995, China 17 billion
U.S. dollars and South Korea 13 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, Japan's exports of chemicals stood at 30
billion U.S. dollars, China's at nine billion U.S. dollars and
South Korea's at 8.9 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
