<HEADLINE> Right-Wing Gains Ground in Norway: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- With little more than one
month remaining before Norway's parliamentary election on
September 15, opinion polls are predicting that the ruling Labor
Party will lose ground, while the far-right Progress Party may be
the big winner, according to a press report here today.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Labor Party led by Prime Minister Thorbjeorn Jagland
has the support of only 28.7 percent of the voters, according to a
recent poll. This result, if confirmed in September, would
represent a sharp decline compared to Labor's 37 percent showing
in the last election.
</P>
<P>
The Progress Party led by Carl Hagen is now supported by 22.7
percent of the electorate. This is a big increase compared to the
6.3 percent vote it gained in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Despite his increased popularity, it is doubtful if the
Progress Party will play a role in the next government. "No other
party wants to talk to me about cooperation. So I will not become
prime minister even I have the second-largest party," said Hagen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
