<HEADLINE> Sharif Vows to Make Pakistan Developed, Prosperous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
today vowed to make "a developed and prosperous Pakistan" for the
coming generations while calling upon the nation for "starting a
new era of development and progress".
</P>
<P>
In a nation-wide address at one minute past midnight to mark
the beginning of the country's Golden Jubilee Day, Sharif said
that "the objective of our efforts and performance will be the
creation of a developed and prosperous Pakistan for our coming
generations."
</P>
<P>
During his 25-minute live-telecast speech, Sharif dwelt at
length on the socio-economic and foreign policies of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the nation's determination to uphold its image and
dignity in the comity of the nations.
</P>
<P>
"We are entering into next half of the century with vigor and
determination, and the time is not far when the ideals of
independence would be realized in letter and spirit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also underlined priorities of his government and said
all possible measures would be taken for economic development and
to improve the living conditions of the people.
</P>
<P>
The world has undergone drastic changes and the strength of the
nations lies not in weaponry but in sound economic base, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Only those who have mastered the fields of science and
technology will move forward," he said. "If we failed to adopt to
these new strategies, we cannot achieve the goal of progress."
</P>
<P>
On Pakistan's relations with other countries, the prime
minister particularly referred to the long and fraternal ties with
China and the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
"Friendship with China is one bright chapter of our history and
the ties with Islamic countries are stronger than before," Sharif
said.
</P>
<P>
"Our role in the Islamic Conference has always been very
effective and will strengthen relations with them in the field of
trade, economy, education, science and research," he said.
</P>
<P>
Relations with the United States were improving and Pakistan
was finding new avenues of cooperation with countries in Europe
and South Asia as well as Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
In respect of relations with India, he said, the government was
trying to take confidence-building measures while reiterating that
Pakistan will continue to give moral, political and diplomatic
support to Kashmiris.
</P>
<P>
"Our independence will complete only when our Kashmiri brothers
will join us in our celebrations," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
