<HEADLINE> More Children Use Hard Drugs in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of pre-teen
children who know their classmates or friends use illegal drugs
more than doubled in the past year, a survey by a private group
said today.
</P>
<P>
The survey, sponsored by the Commission on Substance Abuse
Among America's Adolescents, found that 23.5 percent of
12-year-olds said they knew someone who used hard drugs such as
cocaine or heroin, 122 percent higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The commission, created two years ago by the National Center on
Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University, conducted
the survey by telephone interviews in June and July with a random
sample of 1,115 teens aged 12 to 17. An abbreviated version of the
survey was released today.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government reported that more teen-agers had
tried heroin for the first time last year than ever before. The
Columbia University study showed that heroin use by teen-agers had
doubled between 1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Also the percentage of eighth-graders using marijuana during or
before seventh grade climbed from 7.7 percent to 12.7 percent
between 1992 and 1996 and the use of heroin by teens doubled from
1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
"It is another wake-up call that we have not changed youth
attitudes about drugs which, if unchecked, presage future use,"
said Barry McCaffrey, U.S. President Bill Clinton's drug policy
adviser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
