<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies NATO Forces Trained to Capture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
denied reports that teams of British, U.S. and French commandos
are being trained in Europe to capture Serbian leaders accused of
war crimes in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to what has been reported... U.S. forces are not now
training for or participating in any unilateral or multinational
commando operation to apprehend indicted war criminals in the
former Yugoslavia," Pentagon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The American Broadcasting Company (ABC) news reported Tuesday
night that the teams of commandos are separate from the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and a late fall operation is
expected.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a regular briefing today, Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said that NATO forces have begun
inspecting weaponry held by paramilitary units in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"This is an effort to take forces that we believe should have
been treated as military forces and treating them as military
forces," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
In Bosnia, the so-called Stabilization Forces led by NATO
announced Monday that special police forces will be banned except
for protecting senior elected officials or dignitaries. Any armed
units not certified by the U.N. will be considered illegal.
</P>
<P>
As the deadline of June 1998 for the peacekeeping forces pull
out of Bosnia is approaching, analysts say the U.S. and its allies
are stepping up their efforts to arrest the indicted Bosnian Serb
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. considers former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
as the major obstacle on the road to a full peace in Bosnia and
accuses him as a war criminal, insisting he should be put on
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
