<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Cracks Down Health Care Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Justice Department
study shows greatly increased efforts against health care fraud,
but says the General Accounting Office still estimates "more than
100 billion dollars may be lost in fraud, waste and abuse
annually."
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno listed the problem as a top Justice
Department priority in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Health care fraud investigations by the Federal Bureau of
Investigation rose from 657 in fiscal 1992 to 2,200 last year.
</P>
<P>
Criminal prosecutions rose from 83 cases and 116 defendants in
1992, to 246 cases and 450 defendants last year. Convictions,
including guilty pleas, rose from 90 in 1992 to 307 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Civil health care fraud probes rose from 270 in 1992 to 2,488
last year.
</P>
<P>
The study -- "Department of Justice Health Care Fraud Report,"
says frauds are being committed by every type of health care
provider across the country, and the schemes include billing
frauds, kickbacks and a number of lesser dodges.
</P>
<P>
The report says, "Health care fraud not only costs money, it
also can place patients at risk of serious physical
harm...teenagers... unnecessarily hospitalized because of
kickbacks...senior citizens across the Midwest had medically
unnecessary, poorly fitting knee, leg and back braces," while
others underwent "unnecessary cataract surgery..."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970814.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Consider Visa Requirements for Czech Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada might have to consider
reimposing visa requirements for Czech tourists so as to stop the
growing number of Gypsies seeking refugee asylum here, reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of Gypsy refugee applicants have grown steadily
since Canada removed the requirement for a visa for Czech
nationals in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
And even more Gypsies are expecting to ask for refugee status
in Canada following a Czech television documentary shown last
week, which portray Canada as a generous country for refugees.
</P>
<P>
"It showed Canada as a pretty comfortable country with a pretty
generous assistance and it was perhaps a good idea for Gypsies in
that country to consider moving themselves to Canada," a Canadian
immigration official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many of the Czech Gypsies have acted on the
program's advice and flooded the Czech national airline CSA with
ticket requests.
</P>
<P>
CSA says it has sold three times as many tickets to Canada as
normal since the broadcast ran last Monday. And flights from
Prague to Toronto and Montreal are virtually full until the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Canada received 189 refugee claims from Czechs, of
which only three were approved. The rest are either pending or
have been rejected.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, there were 302
applications for refugee status, of which 38 have been rejected or
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Canada faced a similar situation in 1995 when visa requirements
were removed for Chilean visitors. Thousands arrived seeking
refugee status, causing Canada to reimpose visa requirements.
</P>
<P>
This time, Canada might have to resort to the same solution,
said a senior spokesman for Canada's ministry of immigration and
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"It's not an option we like, but it's always an option," the
spokesman said. "There are other means of correcting this
particular situation, but I cannot say it is not an option."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
